neighborhood_overview: Just minutes by free ferry from Central Station lies Amsterdam North. This neighbourhood is alive and kicking, bursting with cultural hotspots. Authentic urban life lives on, too, still undiscovered by tourists.The Saint Rita church has always been a place where the North comes together. Now, it’s also where you’ll find BUNK Amsterdam. This monumental building is now home to 296 guests, 106 rooms, 50 private pods, eight communal dinner tables and one teddy bear. So come to the North Side, where we have cookies, and company. On top of that, you’ll be sleeping in a church, a unique experience in Amsterdam!
host_about:
BUNK bridges the gap between hotels and hostels by combining affordable luxury rooms and smartly designed private bunk beds.
We converted two monumental churches into meeting places for travellers, locals and artists alike. We host inclusive social events in our sustainable restaurant and other communal spaces.

We aim to redefine hospitality by creating a place for communal wonderment. Where those who wander will start to wonder, triggered by true art, honest food and sincere smiles. We make comfort and design available to everyone, without the need for deep pockets. BUNK is where you can feel free to be your wonderfully weird self as you play your part in new stories you can take home with you.

I'm a doctor living in Amsterdam. I also rent my apartment AirBnB with my girlfriend Laurien.

neighborhood_overview:
Neighborhood Facts
Beginning at Vondelpark and continuing to the Amstel river, the Oud-Zuid and De Pijp neighborhoods have elegant homes on quiet leafy lanes and busy, lively streets with shopping and cafes. The two neighborhoods seem worlds apart but are right next door to each other.

Shopping in De Pijp & Oud-Zuid
Probably the most well-known street market in Amsterdam is the Albert Cuyp Markt, located right in the middle of de Pijp. This market is open six days per week and sells almost anything you might need. Toothpaste, tshirts, fresh pickles, sunglasses, vegetables, cheese, bicycle locks, scarves and stroopwafels are just a few of the items on hand. Albert Cuyp is a wonderful place to get those random items you can’t seem to find elsewhere, like rainbow shoelaces.

On Saturdays don’t miss the ZuiderMarkt, a biological open air market located at the corner of Jacob Obrechtstraat and Johannes Verhulststraat.

neighborhood_overview:
Canal View Amsterdam is beautifully located on the Brouwersgracht at the heart of the monumental 17th Century Canal Belt and on the border of the Jordaan. Brouwersgracht was dug in 1585. In 2007 the quiet and in all seasons splendid Brouwersgracht was choosen by the readers of the Amsterdam newspaper Het Parool as the most beautiful street of Amsterdam. In 2010 the Amsterdam Canal Belt area was placed on the UNESCO World Heritage list.

All major Amsterdam attractions are within walking distance: Haarlemmerstraat / Haarlemmerdijk (1 min.), Jordaan (2 min.), several cosy streetmarkets (4 min.), Nine Streets or Negen Straatjes (5 min.), Anne Frank House (6 min.), Amsterdam Central Station (7 min.), Dam Square (10 min.), concerthall Muziekgebouw aan het IJ (25 min.), Eye Filmmuseum (30 min.).

In the apartment you will find several books about the history of Amsterdam, some tourist guides and also our Folder with a lot more information about restaurants, shops and cult

We really hope that you will feel at home at the Brouwersgracht as much as we do!

neighborhood_overview: In terms of design and development, De Baarsjes is like Oud West: densely populated with few green spaces, but lots of wide streets, squares and facilities. In the 1990s, many neglected buildings were refurbished or replaced by new construction. Mercatorplein was extensively renovated and is the only square completely designed by Berlage that still exists in Amsterdam, thanks to a campaign by residents, which ensured that nothing was demolished. Oud West was a higher priority than De Baarsjes in terms of redevelopment, so De Baarsjes is still lagging in social development by comparison. Even so, it remains a popular neighbourhood with many satisfied residents.

neighborhood_overview:
Our house is right on the edge of the city centre, in the OOSTERPARK area, with it's own vibe and sparkle.
We are close to the zoo (Artis) and just around the corner you find the Oosterpark, the Tropen Museum, relaxed bars (Javastreet area) good food and the famous Windmill Brewery 't IJ.
The Dapper market is our daily market for fresh vegetables, cheese, fish and bread, and also fabric and clothes. Every day between 10-16, not on Sundays.
Several supermarkets around the corner, on the First van Swindenstraat (open from 8-22) and a night shop on Linnaeusstraat (open until 01:00).
host_about:
Once I stayed in a tiny room in the heart of Tribeca, NYC. Outside the window, squashed between brick walls stood a tall tree "planted by Yoko Ono". A memorable sales pitch for a queen-size bed on top of the world. Living on Wooster Street I was a local for a week, a fantastic experience. I would love to offer this kind of experience to my guests when staying in Amsterdam.
The house is mainly occupied by me, my son and Bonnie the cat, but we love to entertain friends and family with food and stories, so the house can be quiet as well as very lively. A family home in short ;-)
Our room for rent is on the second floor of a 4 story house, and with it's own bathroom on the same floor, it is all rather private and relaxed, for the guests as well as us. We live on the two top floors, just a shout away if any help is needed. 
My personal interests are art, photography, film and design, and I love to show my guests the local hotspots. New shows and exhibitions, exciting places to go for shopping, coffee or food, I am happy to share if you want to know. 
I travelled west as far as San Francisco and east as far as Varanasi. Both ways there was always a 'friend's connection' to help out with local stuff. This was before Airbnb existed, and now through this organization I can maybe be that connection for you. Happy to help.
In daily life I am art director, photographer and blogger.

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in a quiet neighbourhood on the boarder of the city centre. It's the perfect location. All the must sees are in a 10/15 minute reach. And when it's time to go home, you will get your sleep and be superfit for the next day.

To enjoy the city as a local, you can rent a bike. Ride your bike to the Van Gogh or Anne Frank museum in 15 minutes. Park it in the red light district, walk around the canals, have a nice meal en let the city take your breath away.
If you feel more like talking a walk. Walk to the Javastraat (Eastside) in 5 minutes and visit one of the newest restaurants or cafe's. Have a surf and turf near the Oosterpark, or grab a IJbeer in the big windmill just around the corner. Also just around the corner, you'll find the best shopping street of 2015 "Czaar Peterstraat". They have cute little boutiques, nice coffee spots, and a great winery.

If you don't feel like walking or taking the bike, there's public transportation all

neighborhood_overview:
Ons huis staat in een 'groene' buurt, 20 minuten van het centrum van Amsterdam (metro). Onze buurt (de Bijlmermeer) grenst aan een groot park met de Gaasperplas, een meer waar je kunt zwemmen en zeilen. Ons huis is de perfecte uitvalsbasis om Amsterdam, Utrecht, andere Nederlandse steden en de natuurgebieden rond Amsterdam te bezoeken. Er is een treinstation en metrostation vlakbij (10 minuten lopen)
De Bijlmermeer is in de jaren 70 gebouwd als "stad van de toekomst" met hoge flats, met relatief ruime appartementen en veel gras, planten, borders en bomen. In de jaren 80 en 90 raakte het gebied in verval, maar sinds de eeuwwisseling floreert Amsterdam Zuid-Oost, met 144 nationaliteiten, een grote bioscoop, het Ajax-stadion en grote en kleine bedrijven. We wonen hier met veel plezier!

We zijn pleegouder geweest van 5 kinderen, die inmiddels niet meer bij ons wonen, maar met wie we nog wel contact hebben. Sinds 2014 zijn we actief op Airbnb en home-exchange en delen we waar we vol van zijn. Als hosts genieten we er oprecht van om gasten uit de hele wereld welkom te heten. Door hen zich thuis te laten voelen in ons huis en onze stad, kunnen wij het leven leiden dat we willen: dynamisch en contrastrijk.

neighborhood_overview:
Discover the beautiful and abundant city of Amsterdam from the heart of its historic city centre right in-between the Central Station and the oldest part of the city, Jordaan. Right behind the house you will find Amsterdam’s famous canals and all it’s other main attractions closeby. The street offers many different food & drink options and even plenty of shops to get great souvenirs. At the end of the street there is an organic food market on Wednesdays (Haarlemmerplein), and on Mondays & Saturdays around the corner at the ‘Noordermarkt’. At the end of the street you will start walking into the commercial shopping area of the city where you will find all major stores and brands.
The ‘Jordaan’ is famous for the 9 Little Streets (9 Straatjes), filled with local boutiques, the Anne Frank house, and local brown cafes. You can easily reach other famous attractions and sights from the house, such as the Dam Palace, Museum District, the flower market, Vondelpark, the Red Light district,

host_about:
Als meisje opgegroeid in het zuiden van Nederland (Limburg) was het altijd een droom om naar de grote stad te verhuizen. In 2010 was het zover. Na het huren van een eerste appartementje midden op de Wallen (Amsterdam Centrum) en de stad verder leren verkennen, vond ik ruim een jaar later ons huidige appartement in Amsterdam Oud-West. Een van de meest populaire buurten onder de Amsterdammers. Met veel plezier heb ik met andere studenten, waaronder vriendinnen, hier gewoond. Sinds 2019 woon ik samen met mijn vriend.
Sfeer, gezelligheid en warme kleuren voeren de boventoon in ons ruime appartement. Het interieur wisselend uit ikea, new design en vintage treasures zijn met veel liefde uitgezocht. De ruime eet- en woonkamer geeft je, na een lange dag door de Amsterdamse straten, het gevoel van thuiskomen. De identieke slaapkamers geven een ultiem gevoel van hotelkwaliteit. De badkamer is voorzien van toiletartikelen en uitgerust met een douche en ligbad. Samen met de luchtzuiverende planten kunt u helemaal tot rust komen. 
Voor de thuischef is de keuken van alle gemakken voorzien. Vanwege de middag- en avondzon kunt u zowel voor als achter op het ruime balkon dineren. 
Bedankt dat u de tijd heeft genomen om ons beter te leren kennen en wij hopen u snel te mogen ontvangen. U bent meer dan van harte welkom!
Liefs, Sophie & Emre

We started this company 20 years ago. In April 2013 we started with renting out through Airbnb. With our experience in letting out to expats from the biggest Multinationals (Shell/Unilever/Johnson&Johnson) we know what people expect in a temporary apartment. 

We try to develop our apartments in a tasteful neutral style with high quality finishing and - furniture on nice locations like the Amsterdam Jordaan Area. Our apartments are not on the busiest places of Amsterdam but always on a maximum 3 minute walk from the canals. 

All our (Amsterdam)apartments are fully licensed by town hall what means that safety is on place 1. Infrared smoke detectors, flight plans, not too many people in 1 flat, no drugs etc.

We try to offer a hotel idea but than in an apartment. So more privacy, luxury, convenience and space on a AAA location but for a better price!

A definite no go is asking for a discount. If our prices are too high I would suggest to rent a bed where the owner was in the night before. 

Also we dont accept guests without any reviews. No exceptions. Sorry.


What is also convenient in our opinion is that we do not live our selves in the apartments. So You dont  sleep on a bed where someone has slept on for 5 years already. 

After every guest the apartments are professionally cleaned and so are  the towels and bedlinen by a professional company.

please see our reviews for confirmation if you are not convinced yet!

neighborhood_overview:
The district is roughly located between the Amstel in the west, the Weespertrekvaart in the east, the Amstel station in the north and the border between Duivendrecht and Amsterdam-Zuidoost in the south. The Duivendrechtsevaart offers a connection for shipping.

The business park, which was developed in the early 1960s, offers space for all kinds of companies and non-heavy industry. The former Bijlmerbajes and the basic rail workplace with an open-air parking facility for GVB buses are located in the district. At the end of the eighties, the Omval was redeveloped, in which besides three office towers also luxury apartments appeared, with which Overamstel had also become a residential area.

Amsterdam West is one of the most buzzing & diverse neighborhoods. You find almost everything there! It's an area with a laid back attitude an home to a cool mix of small stores and many restaurant hotspots. A great diversity of hipster- proof coffee places (to drink coffee, not the type that sells pot ;)), cool concept stores and bars with outside terraces. Amsterdam West is also great for foodies! You find a variety of kitchens and ambiences that will serve every needs.

Furthermore within walking distance you reach the 17th century city centre, while you walk by the cool bars and restaurants before you know it you entered the Jordaan district. Here are the famous UNESCO listed canals like Herengracht, Prinsengracht and Keizersgracht. We are proud to say that our own area has recently been nominated for an UNESCO listing as well, since the archtecture is from a stream of the international Expressionist architecture.

neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam's Jordaan is probably the most famous neighbourhood in the Netherlands.
The Jordaan is nothing but highlights. Maze-like streets offer hidden courtyards, cafés (traditional but also trendy), art galleries and pleasantly noisy neighbours. One also has access to some of the more scenic outdoor markets in the country. In particular, Noordermarkt has a flea market on Monday mornings and an organic farmers' market on Saturdays. There are many more modern, trendy bars around Noordermarkt and along Westerstraat and Rozengracht. The side-streets that run south of Westerstraat have recently developed into a strong culinary district with some of the city’s more highly regarded restaurants.

Liefhebbers voor cultuur, horeca, festivals en vlooienmarkten kunnen hier hun hart ophalen.
Zo is er maandelijkse de grootste vlooienmarkt van Europa (IJhallen), zijn er diverse horeca gelegenheden zoals Pllek, Noorderlicht, IJkantine, Loetje, de Pannenkoekenboot en meer.
De andere kant op, op 10 minuten fietsafstand bevind zich het natuurgebied 't Twiske waar de natuur liefhebber zijn hart kan ophalen. Ook is er veel te beleven voor kinderen met een biologisch dynamische boerderij, avonturenspeelplaats, zwemgelegenheid in natuurwater, kanoën en meer.
Op loopafstand is Noordoogst, een bruisende groene plek rondom de duurzame voedselketen met lokale ondernemers en horeca. Hier is tevens een natuurspeeltuin.

neighborhood_overview: Traditionally a blue collar neighbourhood just a stone's throw away from the heart of town, 'De Baarsjes', is what one calls 'on the rise'. All around us we see new initiatives popping up; from intimate coffee bars and restaurants, to cool boutiques with local designers. Please ask the staff for inside info on where to go!
host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel is a place in Amsterdam where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

On Saturdays the Noordermarkt hosts a local Farmer’s market and on Mondays a Flea Market, and is only a few blocks away as well.

If you decide to rent a bicycle then within a 10-minute cycle you can access the Museumplein where the famous Van Gogh Museum and Rijksmuseum are located. Cycling is one of the best ways to explore the city and enjoy the canals- there are several places you can rent from near to the apartment.

host_about: Wittenberg is a monumental short stay building, offering modern accommodation in Amsterdam's residential area. All apartments are fully equipped, including flat-screen TVs (Smart HD TV), dishwasher, oven, and microwave. Each has its own bathroom with free toiletries and a hairdryer. For your comfort, towels, bed linen and a weekly housekeeping are provided. Some apartments also feature a washing machine and there are public laundry rooms. The Hermitage Museum is just 650 meters away, while Artis Zoo is only 400 meters from Wittenberg. The nearest airport is Schiphol Airport, 12 km away or a 30-minute drive by car.

Boasting 178 nationalities, Oud West is multicultural but is pretty much free of the stereotypes that come with that.

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in the middle of the ''De Pijp'' neighborhood. De Pijp is a hip and happening neighbourhood with a large concentration of restaurants, cafés and bars catering to just about every class and taste.

A few places in Amsterdam have undergone the transformation that de Pijp has gone through in the last 20 years. Once considered a claustrophobic workers neighbourhood with small leaky houses, it’s now home to a multitude of creatives, young families and start ups. It's absolutely exploding with the internationally oriented bars and restaurants to cater to them all with the Albert Cuyp (a seemingly never-ending street market) as the beating heart of it all.

The area is intersected by the Ceintuurbaan, leaving its northern half with the charming Sarphatipark and the southern part with its special Japanese shops and restaurants.

The nearest airport (Schiphol) is about 16 KM from the apartment.

neighborhood_overview: The lively nightspot and market square Nieuwmarkt, found in the old city centre just east of the Red Light District, has been a centre for commerce and socialising in Amsterdam since the 17th century. Created by filling in the surrounding canals, the square's location just inside the old city gate made it a popular spot for traders and shoppers looking for fresh produce. Today, Nieuwmarkt still holds a daily market as well as an organic fare market on Saturdays, but arguably its biggest draw is the amount of cafés, restaurants and coffeeshops that surround it, making this square a perfect place to spend a sunny day sitting on a terrace. The Nieuwmarkt metro stop can be found on the square, which caused quite a bit of protest during its construction but now serves as one of the city's most central and most used stops on the metro service.

neighborhood_overview:
The studio is located in Haarlemmerbuurt - a lively neighbourhood, next to the City Centre. Close to the apartment you can find the Haarlemmerstraat and Haarlemmerdijk streets, known for the great quality and diversity of their shops, boutiques and restaurants.
Moreover, the district borders with the Jordaan neighbourhood in the south - buzzing place with a lot of old Dutch cafes, great restaurants and brick oven pizzerias, boutique design shops, local supermarkets and sight-seeings, such as Westerkerk and the Anne Frank House.

From the apartment you can also easily reach the City Centre and its most famous sight-seeing: the Dam square with the Royal Palace and some famous Amsterdam museums.

Come and enjoy this lovely studio and the great neighbourhood!
host_about:

For a little while I have been running a Bed and Breakfast with the help of my partners at 'BnB Manager'. I live in one of the three rooms we have. 

Around the corner you will be amazed by the view of the Nieuwe Prinsengracht and the Westertoren. To experience Amsterdam in all its glory, you're at the right place at B&B 305. Enjoy the liveliness of the city when you step out, and take a comfortable break when you step in. I'm sure you will enjoy your stay at B&B 305!
property_type: Private room in bed and breakfast

neighborhood_overview:
The house can be found on Realeneiland, a small island that is part of the city centre of Amsterdam, but slightly hidden away from the rest. The realeneiland is part of a group of three islands that together are called 'The Western Isles' (Westelijke eilanden), the two other isles being Bickerseiland and Prinseneiland.

The Western Isles are among the oldest areas of Amsterdam and have a rich history. The house itself is actually one of the fourteen original 'captain's houses' (kapiteinswoningen) of Realeneiland.

The house carries the name 'In 't Anker', which translates as 'in the anchor'; the name along with the house's symbol can be seen on the gable. It can be found on the Zandhoek - the name for the street and corner of the island. As you walk around the neighbourhood you will see boats everywhere, as the island also functions as a small city harbour.
host_about:
Fokko: likes sailing and sitting on the porch with Loes.
Loes : passionate about the German language. Loves being part of the neighbourhood and its people.
We rent out apartments with local hosts (who are on holiday or for other reasons unable to do the checkin themselves) to make your stay in Amsterdam as pleasant as possible!

neighborhood_overview:
The north side is much cheaper than the city to buy groceries, and just about everything else! There are many shops and supermarkets and coffee shops that offer much better prices than in the city which I recommend using.

'Thrillist' have put Amsterdam North on number 3 in their list of the top 10 most 'hipster' neighborhoods on earth! It is surrounded by cool places to drink and party, and only a few minutes from the center.

Amsterdam Noord is currently being built into a 'Smart City' and so many new buildings and streets are being built within a sustainable concept, and interesting individual looking building are popping up all around the North area.

Here in the North side, it is possible to feel like a 'local', with local beers and organic food available in many local restaurants, bars and food/beer festivals.

There are also 2 coffee-shops within walking distance.

neighborhood_overview: The neighbourhood is the most exciting part of Amsterdam. Most of the cultural, entertainment and shopping facilities are in immediate distance. Nevertheless, the building is situated in a quiet corner.
host_about:
H401 is the name of a 17th century canal house in the very centre of Amsterdam at one of the most beautiful canal conjunctions. The house has a stunning history as a hiding place during WWII, but other than the Anne Frank house the building is still used for living and working . In their gallery and studio space H401 features a unique high end cultural programme based on the history of the house that has always been a magnet for artists, writers and people on the move. Castrum Peregrini was the code name during the war and literally translates as 'castle of the pilgrim'. The original hiding place is still preserved and the various floors and spaces represent the houses vibrant history since the 1940s.

We are three friends, Michael, Frans and Lars that run H401 today and we also live in the building, which is big enough to be a universe in itself. We offer three luxurious independent guest appartments, both recently restored in a minimalist manner, with a stunning view to the canal in the front  facing a row of historic 17th century gables and the monumental Krijtberg Church in the back. The rooms offer the unique experience of a historic place with contemprary comfort (state of the art beds, linen, towels etc) The appartments offer equiped kitchens and coffee, tea, and some simple breakfast incredients. Though the accomodations are situated at a quite part of the famous 'gouden bocht' of the Herengracht, the lively and fashionable nine streets are just a stone's throw away; they offer stylish cafes, bars, shops, lunch and diner possibilities. All famous sites and musea are walking distance. Amsterdam at its very best!

neighborhood_overview: Located next to the Mill, Beer brewery, Cheese farm & restaurants of the traditional Dutch village Oud-Sloten, but still in Amsterdam!  Supermarket and shops in walking distance. Recreational lake and park with walking and Cyclingpaths , Houseboats, Bicycle rent shop nearby.
old historic center of Amsterdam is lively with lots of bars and restaurant and plenty things to see. Though my boat is on a qiuet location, so you will sleep well.

The area is very local and unique due to it's variety of small shop owners who are specialist in what the sell or offer :) You can relax in the beautiful Vondelpark or just walk around the area visit no mainstream hidden shops.

The house is in a quiet and residential part of Amsterdam yet the heart of the city can be reached by bus, tram, train, bike or car in 15 mins. Near the house there are fast food (chinese, pizza, fried chicken, kebab) and turkish restaurants, shops (including supermarkets and, drugstores) and parks. You can walk to beautiful parks such as Westerpark and Sloterpas in 20 minutes as well as smaller local parks in less than 5 minutes.

host_about:
I am a realtor since 20 years. Some of my hobbies are travelling,  Ibiza, (race) cycling, my work, cars, soccer and my close friends and family. 

We started this company 20 years ago. In April 2013 we started with renting out through Airbnb. With our experience in letting out to expats from the biggest Multinationals (Shell/Unilever/Johnson&Johnson) we know what people expect in a temporary apartment. 

We try to develop our apartments in a tasteful neutral style with high quality finishing and - furniture on nice locations like the Amsterdam Jordaan Area. Our apartments are not on the busiest places of Amsterdam but always on a maximum 3 minute walk from the canals. 

All our (Amsterdam)apartments are fully licensed by town hall what means that safety is on place 1. Infrared smoke detectors, flight plans, not too many people in 1 flat, no drugs etc.

We try to offer a hotel idea but than in an apartment. So more privacy, luxury, convenience and space on a AAA location but for a better price!

A definite no go is asking for a discount. If our prices are too high I would suggest to rent a bed where the owner was in the night before. 

Also we dont accept guests without any reviews. No exceptions. Sorry.


What is also convenient in our opinion is that we do not live our selves in the apartments. So You dont  sleep on a bed where someone has slept on for 5 years already. 

After every guest the apartments are professionally cleaned and so are  the towels and bedlinen by a professional company.

please see our reviews for confirmation if you are not convinced yet!

neighborhood_overview:
We live in a modern residential area close to the river. There is a lot of modern architecture: one of which is the EYE filmmuseum by DMAA. We are closed in by water, so lot's of boats passing by.

It is a quiet neighborhood, no party area. We are a five minute walk away from the canals and the historic center of Amsterdam.

There are parking facilities on the street or in a public parking but they are (very) expensive. If you want to come by car contact us.

The Pijp is one of the nicest and most trendy areas of Amsterdam, with tons of great restaurants, squares, shops and botiques. The popular Albert Cuyp Market and Sarphatipark are just around the corner. Due to its central location, all the other areas of Amsterdam can be easily reached by bike or public transport. There are a lot of bike rental places at walking distance. Just around the corner of the apartment there is a lovely large playing ground with ping pong tables, picnic tables, and lots of playground equipment, which makes it the perfect place to stay with kids.

The apartment is located in a beautiful location in the heart of De Pijp. The street itself is designed by M. de Klerk and P .L. Kramer, the most important architects of the Amsterdamse School. There is a visitors center at the end of the street which provides tours around the neighborhood in case you want to learn more about the history and iconic architecture!
host_about: Dear (future) guests. I am Sabine, 31 years old and I recently bought this beautiful apartment. After a few months of renovation, it is now completely ready to receive my first airbnb guests. I love hospitality and will do my utmost to make sure you have an unforgettable stay. Always happy to help out with restaurant bookings, recommendations or anything else needed to get the most out of your stay in Amsterdam. Hope we will meet soon!

The beautiful Vondelpark is only a 5 minutes stroll.

The famous museums are less than 10 minutes away by tram or a 15 minutes walk (passing by some of the fanciest shopping streets of Amsterdam - the Cornelis Schuytstraat and the PC Hooftstraat). The Leidseplein is 10 min by bike or tram.

neighborhood_overview:
Oosterpark/Transvaalbuurt area is a multi ethnic neighborhood lately becoming more fancy with bars, restaurant, design shops, attracting more young or young families to live. In this area you can see, taste and smell Amsterdam's and Holland's colonial past. The Museum of the Tropics has exhibitions and performances from all parts of the world all through the year. At the Dappermarket all cultures of Amsterdam are represented. Want to cook Surinamese, Indian, Moroccan, Turkish, Thai or Chinese? Here you can find everything you need.
And of course the Oosterpark (there are 2 more in the area) is a nice retreat to have a walk or jogging in the nature.

neighborhood_overview: The neighbourhood is surprisingly peaceful and green. But at the same time it is in the centre, so close to all amenities and attractions (approx. 5 to 10 minutes walk). Within walking distance from the apartment lie the Hortus Botanicus, the Zoo Artis with its beautiful restaurant from were you can spot the pelicans and flamingos. Walking disctance to the Jewish Historical Museum, the Amsterdam Hermitage Museum, the Rembrandt House, the National Maritime Museum, the Opera, the Red Light District, and many more.
host_about:

I try to contribute to this by my jobs and am dedicated to empower those who have less access to basic goods like water of education.

Groet, Lisette

neighborhood_overview:
Oud-West and in particular De Baarsjes is an upcoming area close to everything the beautiful city of Amsterdam has to offer. It is a 5 minute walk towards the public transport (tram) which takes you within another max of 15 minutes to wherever you wanna go within the city.
If you wanna walk the nearby area you will find both the Vondelpark, as the bustling Kinkerstraat, Jan Pieter Heijestraat & Overtoom within a 5 to 10 minute range.
If you want to feel like a true Amsterdammian or 'Mokummer' as we would say, we would suggest you to rent a pushbike and cruise the city like the rest of us do. You will see that the Jordaan, Damsquare, Leidseplein and Canal area are only a 10 minute bike ride away. There is a good bike rent shop nearby were you can rent bikes for 8,50 euro p/d. A definite must do if possible!

neighborhood_overview: Amsterdam Oud-West is a beautiful and quiet neighborhood just next to the Vondelpark, Amsterdam's biggest public park. On the Overtoom there are a lot of nice restaurants, bars, bike rental shops and a grocery store (Albert Heijn). It takes only 5 minutes by tram or bike to reach Leidseplein, and only 10 minutes to reach the Rijksmuseum or Van Gogh. If you want to see some other nice (not so touristy) neighborhoods, please go to the Jordaan or De Pijp. There you will find al lot of nice little bars, restaurants, street markets and shops.

neighborhood_overview:

Public transport is in walking distance. Trams will take you directly to the major museums like Van Gogh and An Frank (or you can even walk). Tram 4 will take you directly to the RAI congress Center. When you book I will give you my personal restaurant guide with my favourite restaurants.

neighborhood_overview: Our house is in the 'Hallenkwartier', within the Old-West neighborhood. Here you will find many a dynamic mix between the old market on the Ten Katestreet, the FoodHallen, and new and hip shops. All just around the corner!

The College Hotel Amsterdam is one of the hotspots in Oud-Zuid. The hotel is housed in a stylish 19th-century building, which was opened as a school in 1895. Today, the hotel and restaurant continue to contribute to the development of talent; the executive staff consists of students from various hotel schools, who are directed and managed by experienced professionals.

The hotel is located next to the museumsquare, containing the Rijksmuseum, the Stedelijk Museum, the Van Gogh Museum and Moco Museum.
Next to that, the location is well-connected with the public transport you can enter any place in Amsterdam within 10/15 minutes.
Also by foot one can be near the canals in just a few minutes.

The neighbourhood is called 'the Baarsjes'. It is lively, full of bars, restaurants and supermarkets close by. The popular 'De Hallen' (centre for media, culture, fashion, indoor foodmarket and crafts) is 5 minutes by bike or tram.

Our loft is just outside the busy city center. We have 'De Hallen' (Food, film, fashion, crafts and architecture converge at this cultural centre in a converted industrial building), trendy Bars, Restaurants, Galleries, Bakeries, Supermarkets, Coffee Bars and Pubs all around the corner. Also the 'Vondelpark', the 'Ten Katemarkt', Anne Frank House and the 'Museumplein', with the 'Rijksmuseum', Van Gogh Museum, Stedelijk Museum and the new 'Moco' are within walking distance.
And don't forget the "Nine Streets". A shopping area in between the Canals. You will find there all kind of shops, cafes and small restaurants.

You will be staying in the heart of the historical center of Amsterdam, near the Singel on the Canal Belt. You will find many (traditional) bars, cafes, coffeeshops, restaurants and shops on your door step. Within minutes you are on Dam Square (where the Royal Palace and the New Church are located), at the Anne Frank Museum or Amsterdam Museum, at the flower market, in the famous 'Jordaan' area, at the 'Nine Streets' shopping area, in the Haarlemmerstraat, Chinatown, or red light district. The Amsterdam museum district (where the Rijks, Stedelijk and Van Gogh Museums are located) and entertainment/theatre districts Rembrandtplein and Leidseplein, are also easy to reach in about 15 min walk or short tram or bike ride.

The apartment is close to everything that Amsterdam center has to offer! We will share our tips and favourites of Amsterdam with you!
host_about:
We are Brigit and Sebastiaan, a couple in our early 30s from Amsterdam. We both love to travel and been to many places around the world. We love experiencing new cultures and meeting new people and fellow travellers, while we are travelling ourselves, or as hosts via Airbnb. We also love to share our tips and favourites of Amsterdam with you, and are happy to help you planning your trip and activities in Amsterdam.

Besides travelling, we love to read and watch movies, and will share our books and DVD's with you during your stay. 

We look forward to welcoming you in our apartment!
property_type: Private room in bed and breakfast

host_about:
Hi, we are Tim and Marc. We live with our red cat Uluru at the beautiful Weesperzijde in the East of Amsterdam; just a few minutes away from the museum district and the city center and with a splendid view on the river Amstel. We both are journalists. Tim works as a freelance video maker and Marc works at the communication department of the biggest hospital in Amsterdam. 
We love travelling and adventures. From 2005 till 2010, we lived and worked in Sydney, Australia, as freelance correspondents for the Dutch and Belgian media. We love Tintin (Kuifje), we love sports and of course we love cycling. 
So, welcome to Amsterdam and the Weesperzijde!

Only 10 minutes per bicycle to various ferries to the centre.
In 5 minutes walking, bicycling or kayaking you reach the recreation areas and birds resorts of the Waterland, with its pittoresque villages.

The popular Leidseplein just minutes away. Everything on your doorstep, from supermarkets, to delicatessen take away shops, Starbucks, great restaurants, there is just nothing that is not within minutes away at this location. The famous Vondelpark, maybe ten minutes walk, Rembrandtplein, ten minutes, the bustling flowermarket, five minutes. Shoppingstreet Leidsestraat, one minute. Amsterdam's biggest movietheatres, the famous Concert hall, the Stadsschouwburg, all near this location. Bike hire, just around the corner. Booking for trips, on the Leidsestraat.

Can't live without yoga and meditation, music, books, holidays with my family, weekends away with my husband. Life motto: Happiness is being who you are.

neighborhood_overview:
Living on the water gives you a sense of relaxation. Everyday feels like a holiday living here. We swim every day right out of our living room. Also the sunlight bounced by the water gives amazing reflections on the walls and ceiling. At night you can see the beautiful lights of the city centre just sitting on the couch.
Although really close to the city center our street is nice and peaceful. Not to much traffic or tourist around, the kids can play outside under supervision. Right in front of the boat is a little foot and bike bridge which leads to a wonderful park, where you can lay down in de grass or enjoy a good coffee/breakfast/lunch/dinner at Pension Homeland. Or enjoy a beautiful meal at restaurant 'De Scheepskameel'. Only a two minute walk but very popular with locals so a reservation is a must. If you walk a little further west (about 15 minutes) you'll be at the central station, which leads to the mainstream shopping district.
host_about: Happy family of four!

neighborhood_overview: Our home is located next to the most populair area in Amsterdam North, next to NDSM and the ferry to Amsterdam Central Station. We are easy to reach by car and public transport. You can use our 4 bikes,  which will bring you to the city centre in only  15 minutes
host_about: I'm Marieke from Amsterdam, 24 years old.

To make a boat trip, 200m away is already the step.
Experience Amsterdam from the heart of downtown.
Don't forget, because you are right in the middle of Amsterdam it can be somedays a little bit noisy.

neighborhood_overview: Sloterpark, bars & restaurants, winkelcentrum Osdorpplein, WestMarket (foodhall), Theater en Congrescentrum De Meervaart, TKMaxx, H&M, Douglas, ICIParis, McDonald's, World Fashion Centre..wat wil je nog meer?

It’s just a 15 minute walk from Central Station but a whole world away from the hustle and bustle of the vibrant city centre. No wonder the Plantage (or East Canal) district is considered by locals and visitors alike to be one of the best neighbourhoods in this amazing city right now. Hop on a bike or head out for a casual stroll and you’ll find museums, parks,  bars and restaurants along the many canals that crisscross the area.
host_about: Wittenberg is a monumental short stay building, offering modern accommodation in Amsterdam's residential area. Carre Theater and the Dutch National Opera & Ballet are just 500 meters from the property. All other city highlights are easily accessible by pubic transport. All apartments are fully equipped, including flat-screen TVs (Smart HD TV), dishwasher, oven, and microwave. Each has its own bathroom with free toiletries and a hairdryer. For your comfort, towels, bed linen and a weekly housekeeping are provided. Some apartments also feature a washing machine and there are public laundry rooms. The Hermitage Museum is just 650 meters away, while Artis Zoo is only 400 meters from Wittenberg. The nearest airport is Schiphol Airport, 12 km away or a 30-minute drive by car.

neighborhood_overview:
Vondelbuurt

Once you cross the Overtoom you’ll be in the Vondelbuurt, the beautiful, leafy area surrounding the Vondelpark, so named after the playwright Vondel (a sort of Dutch Shakespeare). Points of interest around here include the Hollandse Manege (a riding school hidden away between the façades of upperclass family homes), the Vondelkerk (a circular church in the style of a gothic cathedral), the Vondelpark Open Air Theatre (in summer) and the park itself is always a good place to sit on a sunny day. (Good to know: the Vondelpark was originally built as a recreational area for cyclists so do watch out for the bikes!)

Close to: Stedelijk Museum, Van Gough Museum, Rijksmuseum, MoCo Museum, Food Hallen and the Vondelpark.

neighborhood_overview:
Our neighbourhood (and especially our sunny street) have an exceptional village feel to them. This village connects the city centre to the North and adds to the typical North-Holland ambiance with nearby canals and the historical NDSM warf within walking distance. There you will also find the IJ Hallen, Europe's largest flee market. Nature reserves Twiske and Ilperveld, as well as Waterland and world-famous Zaanse Schans, are just around the corner. On the other hand, you can reach the center of Amsterdam in under 20 minutes, either by bus or on your rental bicycle (riding the free ferry over the IJ just adds to the joy of living in North and we highly recommend this so that you will experience life as a true local! )

From the Central Station, you take the free ferry to NDSM. . If you have a bicycle, you follow the signs to Twiske. From Central Station you can also take bus 35 to Molenwijk. If you are travelling by car, you take exit S118 towards Tuindorp Oostzaan. Another

host_about: Every day on the water is a good day! We are a family of 5. We live on our recently converted house boat Johanna. A new life, full of adventure, in our beautiful and beloved city of Amsterdam.

neighborhood_overview:
We think the best thing about our ship is the fact that it's in the center of Amsterdam, but not on the busy canals. So you won't be bothered by people on little or big boats that will float by. The ship is situated in the oldest part of Amsterdam, with the old canalhouses where Amsterdam is famous for. If you walk underneath the railway track, you're immediately in the busy streets of Amsterdam: the Jordaan.
A big supermarket is at 200 feet distance and all sorts of nice shops in the Haarlemmerstraat (best shopping street of Holland 2012).
We have a bicycle which you can use, so you can see all of Amsterdam.
host_about:
We are a family of three, living on our ship in Amsterdam. If you have any special requests for your stay or need information on places to go, eat, drink, please do not hesitate to drop us a line. We will try to answer you as best as we can to make your stay as pleasant and comfortable as possible.

Our ship was build in 1899 and originally used for transportation. Many years ago it was transformed into a beautiful houseboat and now located in the centre of Amsterdam. The Haarlemmerstraat, which was called the best shopping street in The Netherlands in 2012, is 300 meters away. Central Station is within walking distance.
Our ship is docked in the oldest part of Amsterdam: Prinseneiland / Jordaan. 
We have a quay, next to the ship, where you can relax in the sun, till late in the evening. We also have a fire pit at the quay, so you can extend those lovely nights....

We have a big kitchen, with dishwasher, microwave, freezer, etc.
The livingroom is big as well, we have a television, wifi, WII and a wood stove.
In the front of the ship is one (large) bedroom with a bed for two persons and in the back of the ship is also a bed for two persons, a little bit bigger than the other bed.
We have a bathroom with a bathtub and shower.
Washing machine is also available on the ship.
We have two cats. They are both lovely and will stay on the ship.

We have a natural fence of plants around the water, so it is quite safe for little kids. But we also have life vests for the little ones, which is advised.

The ship is docked and not able to sail anymore, so you don't have to be afraid of waking up in the middle of the canal ;)

All in all a great opportunity to experience the Dutch live on a houseboat!

neighborhood_overview: The "vogelbuurt" was one of the first extension of Amsterdam towards the north. It's built in the 1920's and still has the atmosphere of a small town. Because it's close to the river IJ you are only 10 minutes from the city center. In the last couple of years the north is getting more vibrant with restaurants bars and f.i. Eye film museum.

The YAYS Amsterdam Maritime is located in the eastern part of town. Mixing museum classics with nightlife hotspots frequented by the city’s hippest, Amsterdam-Oost truly offers something for everyone. Get your cultural fix at the Tropenmuseum, the Botanical Gardens or the Maritime Museum. If you like your sights to be a little more alive, visit Artis Magistra –the oldest zoo in the Netherlands. Then ease into the evening with a locally brewed beer at Brouwerij ‘t IJ before grabbing dinner in one of the many bars around the Oosterpark - all within walking distance from the apartment.
host_about:

neighborhood_overview:
The Pijp is located directly south of Amsterdam's city centre and it is part of the borough 'Amsterdam-Zuid'. Most street names in the Pijp are named after famous Dutch painters.
The most famous and busiest street market of the Netherlands, the Albert Cuyp Market, is in the Pijp. It is open six days per week and attracts a lot of tourists. The former Heineken brewery is also a popular tourist attraction. Next to the former Heineken brewery is the Marie Heinekenplein, which has a lot of bars and cafes, as well as the near Gerard Douplein.
It used to be Piet Mondriaan's neighborhood back in the day. And many call it the Quartier Latin of Amsterdam for its great vibe and livelyhood.

Traditionally a blue collar neighbourhood just a stone's throw away from the heart of town, 'De Baarsjes', is what one calls 'on the rise'. All around us we see new initiatives popping up; from intimate coffee bars and restaurants, to cool boutiques with local designers. Please ask the staff for inside info on where to go!
host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel is a place in Amsterdam where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

neighborhood_overview: This apartment is located in Nieuwmarkt in the centre of Old Amsterdam. Nieuwmarkt square is filled with shops, cafes, bars and the popular market. It is home to De Waag, an old weight house that used to form part of the city walls constructed in 1481. During the 16th century boats would stop here, unload their goods, weigh them and pay the required taxes. Today the building houses a restaurant and is a great place to stop for a drink on a warm afternoon. The centre of Amsterdam, Dam Square, can be reached on foot and is home to the stunning Royal Palace, Madame Tussauds, the New Church and De Bijenkorf department store. For art lovers Rembrandt House is just a short distance from the apartment and it is here he lived and worked for many years. Many of the major attractions are within walking distance of the apartment, while the Metro and trams provide public transport options allowing you to get to any part of the city with ease.

host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel is a place in Amsterdam where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

Bos en Lommer, also known as BOLO :), is an upcoming neighbourhood just west of Amsterdam's city centre within the centre ring.

It has all the good stuff, excellent public transportation, affordable parking (Q-Park Bos en Lommer), nice and affordable places to eat, 3 supermarkets (Albert Heijn open until 22 pm), 2 banks, a few clothingshops, a daily outside market on the Bos en Lommerplein, a library, a gym which allows 1-day entrance, a bike rental shop, all within 2 minutes walking distance.

Places to have diner nearby:
Wilde Westen and Buurman&Buurman (nice pizza's!), Podium Mozaiek, Tokio Sushibar (great sushi for delivery at home), Snackbar Pittstop (try the frikandel and kroket!), Thai food (Kratiam), Turkish food (Meram and Bir Tat), Italian (Michelangelo & Domino's Pizza), Café Zurich and the newly opened Tajine Bar on Mercatorplein and of course the KFC across the street.

Fascinating to see how the skateboarders from our city enjoy themselves here. Or do you want to try it yourself? IJburg is about the same distance in an easterly direction. The apartment is located in the Rivierenbuurt, a trendy neighbourhood situated in the Southeastern part of Amsterdam bordered by the river Amstel. Here you can find a nice mixture of young professionals, students and families and where you can experience how it really is to live in Amsterdam among the locals. It is safe and an oasis of calm in the centre of the city. Explore the beautiful surrounding by bike or foot along the river Amstel or visit the beautiful nearby Amstel and Beatrix park.

neighborhood_overview: IJburg is a popular place to enjoy watersports and a variety of facilities can be found at the harbour, which lies just 400 metres from the apartment. Several restaurants, bars and activity centres for children can be found along Blijburg beach.

The continuously developing Amsterdam Noord has a lot to offer. Don’t miss out on the popular EYE Film Museum, a stunning piece of architecture along the IJ river. Next door you’ll find the A’dam Tower, where from the top you can oversee Amsterdam and its many neighbourhoods and beautiful canals.

NDSM is a creative hub, with many popular events happening every year. In summer, this is a spot where locals come to dine and socialize at one of the many trendy terraces and bars. And the city centre of Amsterdam is only a short ferry ride away.

The Jordaan is the most popular area of Amsterdam. In former days it was an area for the working lower class. Nowadays its a vivid area full of pitoresque canals , buidings and nightlife. You can walk to the most main events in Amsterdam; Anne Frank House, Dam square, Leidse square, museum area, canals and the red light district

host_about:
We are conscious about the choices we make. That is why there is sustainability in everything that we do, without compromising comfort. And our stylish hotels and restaurants each have their own unique style and story, which makes every visit a special experience. We do it differently by nature.

We have been around for over 10 years now, making us pioneers in eco-friendly tourism.

We do it differently by combining stylish design and playfulness with sustainability, calling it Eco-Sexy. This is felt throughout your entire stay. From small notes in the rooms that tell guests about the recycled furniture and water-saving showers to every bite and drink that are served being fully organic. There is no stopping us delivering the eco choice while maintaining a high level of comfort.

neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood (the Plantage) is a small green village in the center of Amsterdam. There is a mix of people: students, families, the elderly, tourists, artists and writers. Artis is a one minute walk. In the morning you can hear the monkeys! The Hortus Botanicus is just as close.

De Plantage is an old Jewish neighborhood with several memorial monuments. Our house is located at the Wertheimpark, the oldest park in Amsterdam. Children can play there and you can enjoy a picnic. The oldest center of Amsterdam is a 15-20 minute walk away. Our guests are very enthusiastic about the neighborhood, which is quiet, but very close to the center. Check the reviews!

The PIJP is amsterdams liveliest centrally located area just off the centre. Our apt is located 1 minute from
Sarphati Park and 5 minutes walk to the famous Albert Cuyp Market, Rembrandt and Van Gogh Museum and its many most amazing restaurants and bars. The hood is known for its bohemian vibe. Amsterdam vibes but feels like a small cosy neighbourhood. No taxis needed.
All landmarks are just a short walking (or tram-metro- cycling) distance away whilst you feel you are in a comfortable
neighbourhood.

This area is called the Bongerd (orchard of apple trees) and is part of the bigger area ‘Tuindorp-Oostzaan’ (garden village). Bongerd means orchard, so all our streetnames are names of different sorts of apples, like our street ‘Kaneelappelstraat’ (apple cinnamon street).This neighbourhood has been built in the last 7 years.

We live very close to the NDSM-wharf, which is in the Top-10 of the hippest area's in Europe. This used to be a harbour. You can still see an old crane at the end of the street, which had been used for building 80% of the houses that are in this area as of the 1950s. Even the new York times wrote about it as one of the world's top 10 hip places in the world.
The area still feels like a village: human scale housing, a lot of green and parks (it is the greenest area in Amsterdam).
The van der Pekbuurt is also still one of the poorest area's in Amsterdam. And a lot of other area's in the North are. But it is getting mixed now, and the mix is a nice one.

neighborhood_overview:
The Jordaan is a famous district in the center of Amsterdam. Originally it was a working-class neighborhood, but now the Jordaan is one of the most expensive locations in Amsterdam.

Most of the streets and canals are named after flowers and trees. It is a cosy neighborhood with many traditional cafes, art galleries, modern art and specialty shops and restaurants.

Many houses have inner courtyards, the courtyards were built by rich people for elderly women. There are 3 markets in this district; the Noordermarkt, there is a market at the Westerstraat and at the Lindengracht. Around these areas there are a lot of traditional cafes and bars.

The world famous Anne Frank Huis is located in this district. It is a biographical museum dedicated to Anne Frank, who was a diarist during the Second World War.

You are in the beautiful Haarlemmerbuurt, which is located amazingly in Amsterdam: Close to the center, but away from the main tourist crowds. With Westerpark right next door, little community gardens, canals filled with houseboats and even a petting zoo in the neighborhood, it’s a lovely green area, especially in summer!

A 2 minute walk towards the city and you are right in the middle of Haarlemmerdijk, where you will find some of the cutest shops in Amsterdam and great places to eat out or get takeaway.

Just a few blocks down from Haarlemmerdijk, you are in Jordaan – pass by Anne Frank House, the Royal Palace and you are in the middle of the old town of Amsterdam.

On hot summer days it’s a paradise for swimmers, but also on cloudy days the Weesperzijde in Amsterdam East is one of the most beautiful spots of the city! It’s there where you catch the last sun beams of the day and the view is amazing.

You can find some typical 19th century buildings in this area, so you will get the Amsterdam feeling when you stay here!

It's very close to Station Amsterdam Amstel and about 200 m. to Metrostation.

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in the middle of the ''De Pijp'' neighborhood. De Pijp is a hip and happening neighbourhood with a large concentration of restaurants, cafés and bars catering to just about every class and taste.

A few places in Amsterdam have undergone the transformation that de Pijp has gone through in the last 20 years. Once considered a claustrophobic workers neighbourhood with small leaky houses, it’s now home to a multitude of creatives, young families and start ups. It's absolutely exploding with the internationally oriented bars and restaurants to cater to them all with the Albert Cuyp (a seemingly never-ending street market) as the beating heart of it all.

The area is intersected by the Ceintuurbaan, leaving its northern half with the charming Sarphatipark and the southern part with its special Japanese shops and restaurants, crowned by the presence of the Okura hotel and its multiple (Japanese) Michelin starred restaurants.

host_about:
BUNK bridges the gap between hotels and hostels by combining affordable luxury rooms and smartly designed private bunk beds.
We converted two monumental churches into meeting places for travellers, locals and artists alike. We host inclusive social events in our sustainable restaurant and other communal spaces.

We aim to redefine hospitality by creating a place for communal wonderment. Where those who wander will start to wonder, triggered by true art, honest food and sincere smiles. We make comfort and design available to everyone, without the need for deep pockets. BUNK is where you can feel free to be your wonderfully weird self as you play your part in new stories you can take home with you.

De Vondelbuurt is een luxe buurt in stadsdeel Amsterdam-West, en heeft veel te bieden. Zo kun je makkelijk een wandeling maken in het Vondelpark, sporten in een van de sportscholen of lekker uitgaan in een van de vele restaurants, cafés of nachtclubs. De Vondelbuurt heeft het allemaal!

Geschiedenis van de Vondelbuurt
Opening van het Vondelpark
In 1865 werd het Vondelpark geopend, en dit was het begin van de Vondelbuurt. Het park werd namelijk aangelegd om de waarde van de toekomstige omliggende huizen te verhogen.

De Vondelbuurt was toen nog een relatief kleine buurt. In de Tweede Wereldoorlog namen de Duitsers het Vondelpark in beslag, en werden diverse delen van de omliggende wijk vernietigd. Na de oorlog, in 1953, kwam het Vondelpark in bezit van de Gemeente Amsterdam.

De start van een elegante buurt
De Vondelbuurt werd na de Tweede Wereldoorlog helemaal opgeknapt. Ook begon er in 1958 een tram te rijden, en werden

host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

neighborhood_overview:
Living by the canal - that is a dream for many. In the past, however, this was considered frowned upon and not classical enough. Therefore the canal was filled up around 16th century. A beautiful park in the middle of the city was created - and still is today. Large trees that provide shade in summer and absorb the sounds of the city.
I love the Cafe Slijterij Oosterling (50m from us). Open since 1877, this is probably one of the most authentic places in Amsterdam. Time seems to stand still here. If you are hungry, you can get delicious sandwiches, burgers, salads or freshly caught fish in the Brasserie Nel (400m). If you prefer self-catering and our shared kitchen, the supermarket is only 70m away.

property_type: Private room in bed and breakfast

neighborhood_overview: Oud-Zuid is a well-to-do neighbourhood in the centre of Amsterdam. It is a largely residential district, characterised by the 1920's Dutch art-deco style housing, called Amsterdamse School. A number of the city's famous museums, such as Van Gogh, Stedelijk and Rijksmuseum are housed here, as is the Royal Dutch Concerthall, home to the world-renowned Concertgebouw Orkest. The area also has ample options for wining and dining, through its characteristic coffee houses, (brown) cafes and the many restaurants and it has several boutique shopping streets, including our own address, that attract high-heeled shoppers from around the country.

host_about: Hi, I am Maaike, living in Amsterdam and love to travel and explore new places!

neighborhood_overview: Oud Zuid is central: on one end you have Amsterdam’s nightlife and culture square Leidseplein and on the other Amstelveenseweg that is developing into a true culinary boulevard. And throughout the neighbourhood, a new bar seems to pop up every week. But for residents, firm favourites remain Vondelpark’s Vondelpark3 and Blauwe Theehuis. The Vondelpark remains Amsterdam’s most densely populated place-to-be whenever the sun shines. Besides this it’s nice to live near one of the greatest overviews of Western Art in the world. Two of the main museums, the Rijksmuseum and the Stedelijk Museum. For big shopping streets you can go to the PC Hooftstraat, Jacob Obrechtstraat, Cornelis Schuytstraat and Beethovenstraat.

neighborhood_overview: The Jordaan is possibly the most famous neighbourhood in the Netherlands. This once working-class bastion was renowned for tight community bonds, radical politics and a love for drink and over-the-top sing-a-longs. Gentrification of decades past has attracted more galleries, restaurants, specialty shops and upwardly-mobile residents to its scenic streets, but there’s undeniably still a distinct atmosphere to be enjoyed here.

neighborhood_overview:
H401 is situated at a historic canal district in the most prestigious part of Amsterdam, right in-between the 'Gouden Bocht' (golden bent) and The Nine Streets - De Negen Straatjes, one of the city’s most delightful shopping areas. These picturesque streets straddle the 17th Century canals from the Singel to the Prinsengracht.
Spend a fabulous day wandering from one to the next exploring the designer boutiques, art galleries, jewellers, gift shops, fashion shops and specialist businesses - there are plenty of great bars, cafes and restaurants to refresh you along the way... And last but not least: all famous museums are within walking distance.
host_about:
H401 is the name of a 17th century canal house in the very centre of Amsterdam at one of the most beautiful canal conjunctions. The house has a stunning history as a hiding place during WWII, but other than the Anne Frank house the building is still used for living and working . In their gallery and studio space H401 features a unique high end cultural programme based on the history of the house that has always been a magnet for artists, writers and people on the move. Castrum Peregrini was the code name during the war and literally translates as 'castle of the pilgrim'. The original hiding place is still preserved and the various floors and spaces represent the houses vibrant history since the 1940s.

We are three friends, Michael, Frans and Lars that run H401 today and we also live in the building, which is big enough to be a universe in itself. We offer three luxurious independent guest appartments, both recently restored in a minimalist manner, with a stunning view to the canal in the front  facing a row of historic 17th century gables and the monumental Krijtberg Church in the back. The rooms offer the unique experience of a historic place with contemprary comfort (state of the art beds, linen, towels etc) The appartments offer equiped kitchens and coffee, tea, and some simple breakfast incredients. Though the accomodations are situated at a quite part of the famous 'gouden bocht' of the Herengracht, the lively and fashionable nine streets are just a stone's throw away; they offer stylish cafes, bars, shops, lunch and diner possibilities. All famous sites and musea are walking distance. Amsterdam at its very best!

host_about:
Welcome at Mi BnB, our B&B in Amsterdam West! We started in May 2017 and have had lots of guests from all over the world since then.

Mi BnB offers 2 simple rooms, the larger "Nice Room" on the 1st floor and the "Cozy Room" our tiny room on the ground floor. 

Each room has it's own small private bathroom, a smart tv,  coffee & tea facilities and a fridge. The 2 rooms share the front door and a small hall.

The B&B is in our family home in a nice, quiet, green neighbourhood, with excellent public transport around the corner. It is only half an hour to the city centre and all the tourist attractions are easy to reach by bus, tram or bike!

In Amsterdam it is only allowed to run a B&B when the owner lives in the house as well. So we are also living in the house with our children and our German Sheppard.

Please don't expect silence! At night it is quiet in general after 22h.

I love to meet new people from over the world and to speak foreign languages like English, Spanish, Italian and a little Portuguese, French and German.

We rent bikes for 10 euro per bike per day. 

Hope to meet you soon! 
Michèle  - Mi BnB

.

Welcome to Amsterdam!

During The Golden Age the Watergraafsmeer was the polder where merchants built their out of town residents, and some of that airy, stately atmosphere is still contained. Frankendael, now turned over in a great restaurant (do eat lunch on their wonderfull terrace in summer) on the Middenweg, is the one example that has survived. There's a wonderfull garden and town park adjacent.
You don't even have to go to the citycenter to spend a wonderfull time in Amsterdam: the Watergraafsmeer (and the other eastern parts of Amsterdam) is a very popular neighbourhood, full of hipster cafés and trendy restaurants, a list of which we will provide. You can look for great architecture at the nearby Indische buurt, and the Eastern Islands. There are great parks to relax and sport close by: the kid friendly Frankendael, the Flevopark (great for running) and Oosterpark.
For your daily groceries: the C. Huijgensplein is 5 minutes from our home, the Middenweg just about 10. Here you can find supe

neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam Old-West is one of the most popular neighborhoods in Amsterdam. It is very lively, but not overcrowded or noisy. Moreover, it is located conveniently, close to shops, restaurants, cafes, museums and touristic attractions. To give you an idea:

- Grocery store: within 250m
- Cafes and restaurants: too many to list, but I can advise you when you get here
- Laundry service: across the street
- Local market: every day, in the street of the apartment
- Cinema: next door
- Food Halls: next door
- Parks: multiple parks are within 1-1,5 km distance
- Public transportation: tram 17 and 7 stop 50m from the apartment
- Touristic attractions and museums: typically within 0-3km (e.g. Anne Frank House would be 2km, Museum Quarter would be 1,5km, Amsterdam Canals are within 1km)

This apartment is located in the "Hoofddorpplein" neighbourhood, which is located in the district "Amsterdam-Zuid".

The neighborhood was built in the twenties. The characteristic architectural style can be found everywhere in the streetscape, such as the eccentric housing porticoes and the pointed corner towers.

Two beautiful parks, Vondelpark and Rembrandtpark, are just around the corner: 5 minutes by bike or 15 minutes walk.
In the summer, you can relax (and even swim!) at the Stadiongracht or in Park Schinkeleilanden.

This quiet neighborhood is popular with families, students and couples. It is very conveniently located near the station Amsterdam-Zuid where all train, metro, and tram connections are available. Also the neighborhood is surrounded by the A10 so you will be on the highways in no time. Schiphol Airport is only at 10 minutes from the apartment by car.

neighborhood_overview:
The Jordaan is a neighbourhood of the city of Amsterdam, Netherlands. It is part of the borough of Amsterdam-Centrum. The area is bordered by the Lijnbaansgracht canal to the west, the Prinsengracht to the east, the Brouwersgracht to the north and the Leidsegracht to the south. The former canal Rozengracht (now filled in) is the main traffic artery through the neighbourhood.Originally a working-class neighbourhood, the Jordaan has become one of the most expensive, upscale locations in the Netherlands. It is home to many art galleries, particularly for modern art, and is also dotted with speciality shops and restaurants. Markets are held regularly at Noordermarkt, the Westerstraat (the Lapjesmarkt textile market) and Lindengracht.

Rembrandt spent the last years of his life in the Jordaan, on the Rozengracht canal. He was buried in the Westerkerk church, at the corner of Rozengracht and Prinsengracht, just beyond the Jordaan. The Anne Frank House, where Anne Frank went into hi
host_about:

neighborhood_overview:
Spiegelkwartier

The Spiegelkwartier is the Art and Antiques district in Amsterdam.
Here you’ll find more than 70 antiques dealers and art galleries, together offering a resplendent array of fine historical objects, classic and contemporary art, and exotic folk art.
You will find also restaurants, casual eateries and cosy cafés on almost every corner.
The Spiegelkwartier is located between the Herengracht and the Rijksmuseum.

www.spiegelkwartier.nl

Museum Quarter

The Amsterdam Museum Quarter is home to the three most important museums in the Netherlands: the Rijksmuseum, the Stedelijk Museum and the Van Gogh Museum.
It also houses the majestic Concertgebouw and some superb cafés and restaurants.
With its large grassy open area, the Museumplein offers plenty of room to have a picnic or just relax. The Museum Quarter even has its own indoor swimming pool.

neighborhood_overview: Our neighbourhood is in the sunny side of the river IJ that crosses Amsterdam. Amsterdam's north side is undergoing a rapid transformation of gentrification where industry, varying from wharves to small scale car shops, is making place for houses. Our specific neighborhood has been residential since the early 20th century. Although in our street there are three older farms, one going back as far as the 17th century. It has a very cosy and private feeling, with many gardens, an old dyke, a canal and it still has a certain rural atmosphere. But as said before; Central Sation is 15 minutes by bike, from there on you easily walk or bike almost anywhere in Amsterdam since it is a very compact city. You can obviously also connect to almost all trains, trams, busses and metro.
Sweet neighbors, great atmosphere, safe and quiet street, walking to parks, playgrounds, shops, bars and public transport. Lively down town Amsterdam is a 10 minute bike or tram ride away.
host_about: Welcome! I live with my husband and our three boys (5, 7 and 9 years of age) in this lovely area. We feel happy and at home ever since we moved in here 10 years ago. The neighborhood is quiet, and at the same time their is so much happening a stepping stone away. Great shops, several grocery stores, local bars and restaurants and public transport to down town. And of course 'our' two lovely city parks where we play ball with the boys or hang out on one of the monthly markets. In our free time we travel as much as possible, with our little camper van. Through the countryside in the weekends, or further south in Europe during school holidays. In these periods we rent our our house and wish they feel at home as much as we do.

neighborhood_overview: You will be staying in the seventeenth-century canal ring area of Amsterdam. Which is on the Unesco’s World Heritage list. Within only a few minutes walking distance you will find, Dam square, the Anne Frank house and Amsterdam’s largest shopping area. The B&B is located in the 9 streets area of the canal ring. The quaint and quirky streets that straddle Amsterdam’s grandest canals form the city’s most photogenic micro-neighbourhood. Known to locals as De Negen Straatjes or ‘The Nine Streets’, this special neighbourhood is full to bursting with vintage and designer shopping, speciality stores and cosy cafés. Because of the big windows a lot of light is allowed to enter the room and give you a chance to take a look at the gardens of the typical Amsterdam homes and even a glance at the Westertoren. Anne Frank wrote in her diary that she could see the tower of the Westerkerk (the church) and hear the bells chiming.
