neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam's Jordaan is probably the most famous neighbourhood in the Netherlands.
The Jordaan is nothing but highlights. Maze-like streets offer hidden courtyards, cafés (traditional but also trendy), art galleries and pleasantly noisy neighbours. One also has access to some of the more scenic outdoor markets in the country. In particular, Noordermarkt has a flea market on Monday mornings and an organic farmer's' market on Saturdays. There are many more modern, trendy bars around Noordermarkt and along Westerstraat and Rozengracht. The side-streets that run south of Westerstraat have recently developed into a strong culinary district with some of the city’s more highly regarded restaurants.

The apartment is located in “De Jordaan”. The Jordaan is a district in the citycenter of Amsterdam, known for its original canal houses, nice restaurants and authentic little shops. When in Amsterdam, it is a must to stroll through the canals and it’s historical streets.
Popular streets in the Jordaan are the Prinsengracht, the Westerstraat, Haarlemmerstraat and the '9 straatjes' (nine little streets).
On the many bridges over the canals, you can take beautiful pictures and see why Amsterdam is called the Venice of the North.

You can still enjoy the city-center and these streets during the COVID-19 situations. Coffeeshops are open for take-away. Restaurants and bars are using their outdoor stand in order to serve your food and drinks on the go!

Perfect athmosphere for the perfect time!

neighborhood_overview: The Westerpark is of course the hotspot in the area. This large park has everything: sports fields, fountains for bathing, barbecue areas and various sunbathing areas. Until the 1960s, gas was still being produced on the Westergasterrein. Now, mainly cultural activities take place: The Ketelhuis screens films, in other buildings there are cafes, restaurants, TV studios and clubs where you can dance until late.

The ship is located on the river Amstel which connects to the canals, and is close to the Pijp a trendy neighborhood with cool bars, restaurants and shops. Perfect if you are looking to avoid the more touristy areas.

Amsterdam-Noord is an authentic neighborhood that is going through a booming transformation over the past years due to the high prices of the city center. Very trendy and sustainable venues have been opened, maintaining the industrial vibe. If you want to go deeper than the typical tours around the city canals you will find a large variety of options without leaving the area.

neighborhood_overview: De Pijp district is one of the most cosmopolitan and vibrant districts of Amsterdam. Formerly a working class quarter built to ease the overpopulated Jordaan in the 19th century and to house laborers, de Pijp as we Amsterdammers know it today is without doubt a melting pot of cultures and nationalities. You can indulge yourself for hours in Amsterdam’s lively Latin Quarter, with its colorful mix of cuisines, terraces and convivial cafés. From the beautiful landscaped gardens of Sarphatipark to the famous Albert Cuypmarkt street market, De Pijp oozes beatnik flair from every angle. Our apartment is on a quiet residential street in the New Pijp, around the corner from Van Woustraat, where you will find cafes, restaurants, supermarkets, local shops and great tram connections. The heart of the city and RAI convention centre are both reachable in less than 15 minutes by tram.
host_location: De Pijp, North Holland, The Netherlands

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located really close to the Jordaan Area. The Jordaan district is the city center of Amsterdam, known by its beautiful houses, nice restaurants and shops. The canals of Amsterdam are located here as well.

In the Jordaan, there are several markets you can visit. Every Monday, there is a flea market at the Noordermarkt. It is the perfect spot to buy Dutch plates, pots and linen. They are also selling clothes and accessories. For a foodmarket, you can go to the Lindenmarkt at the Lindengracht on Saturdays, to the Westerstraat market on Mondays or to the Biological foodmarket at the Noordermarkt on Saturdays.

The Westertoren is one of the landmarks of the Jordaan. It's really worth to visit and climb! Also close by: Anne Frank Huis, Dam, Royal Palace.

host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

neighborhood_overview:

The center, Amstel and Central Station and De Zuidas are quickly and easily accessible. Shops for daily groceries (and more) at the Linnaeusweg, Middenweg and Beukenplein are right around the corner. There is a market for fresh and cheap produce 6 days a week (Dappermarkt) close by. You can walk to the Amstel and of course the Oosterpark which is right across the street. You can cycle to the center or De Pijp in just 10 minutes. The Amstel is 5 minutes by bike, the Tropenmuseum is a 5 minute walk through the park, as is Artis (city Zoo).

neighborhood_overview: Consisting of multiple artificial islands that are connected by bridges over canals, the city’s most recent expansion area ‘IJburg’ still feels like the real Amsterdam. All in all there’s much to do on the island itself, but if you feel like visiting other areas in Amsterdam, tram 26 takes you directly to Amsterdam Central Station in about 30 minutes.

neighborhood_overview:
review of New York Times:

FOOD HALL FAME, 2 P.M.

To be a cutting-edge European capital these days, having an impressive indoor food hall is practically a prerequisite. Enter Amsterdam’s Foodhallen, which opened in a former tram depot in 2014 with about two dozen stalls, many occupied by well-known local businesses. For lunch, hit the highlights, starting with De BallenBar’s truffle bitterballen (traditional Dutch croquettes) and a local craft beer like the chile-and-coriander-infused Thai Thai Tripel from Oedipus Brewing. Then proceed to Viet View for a stupendous banh mi with caramelized pork belly with cucumber, pickled carrots and daikon. Finish with a drink at the gin-and-tonic bar, where the made-in-Holland Vording’s Gin is served in a Spanish-style goblet garnished with red-apple slices and a cinnamon stick. Lunch for two, about €30.

Lovely area to walk around in with friends, dogs or alone. Next to the park and in the middle of wetlands you can use for kayaking and swimming.

The property is located between Brouwersgracht and Rozengracht, near Multatuliplein. The Singel forms part of the famous Amsterdam canals and has now been inscribed on the Unesco World Heritage list. Singel is the innermost (main) canal and is within walking distance of Haarlemmerstraat, Noordermarkt, Dam square and the popular 9 straatjes shopping area. This charming and bustling part of De Jordaan is still very authentic and offers something for everyone: a great variety of bars, restaurants and boutiques, and, if you like to engage in sports, Westerpark is within easy walking distance. This area also offers the opportunity to engage in a variety of cultural activities, for example at the Concertgebouw and the internationally renowned Rijksmuseum, Stedelijk Museum and Van Gogh Museum. You can also find the Anne Frankhuis and the famous Westertoren in de Jordaan nearby.
The area has excellent public transport links (trams and buses) and the A-10, A-2, A-9 and A-4 motorways as wel

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in de so called ''Indische Buurt''. It is a neighbourhood filled with cosy restaurants, cinema etc. and all kinds of other shops are nearby.
The Dappermarkt is one of the country’s oldest - and best - outdoor markets. It forms the multicultural heart of the neighbourhood along with the hip and happening Javastraat, which once only provided every manner of global grocery but is now beginning to feature more upscale cafes and terraces. One of the city’s largest general hospitals, OLVG, is also located here. Two stellar city parks, Oosterpark and Flevopark, provide quick escape from the relatively busy streets. Besides many cheap ethnic eateries and supermarkets, the area is attracting much more higher-end cafes and restaurants who are often reinventing many of the area’s industrial monuments. On sunny days, the parks and terraces are filled with locals.

Welcome to De Pijp.
It’s one of the older neighbourhoods of Amsterdam. It has a lot of nice coffee places to go, trendy boutiques, shops and bars.

De Pijp is brimming with fantastic (typical Dutch) cafés, restaurants, coffee shops and bars. Of course, a visit to Amsterdam wouldn’t be the same without a trip to the famous Albert Cuypmarket, flanked by over 100 shops. If you wander down Albert Cuypstraat, Gerard Doustraat and Ferdinand Bolstraat, the main streets in de Pijp, you'll find many exotic and authentic Syrian, Moroccan, Surinamese restaurants, to name but a few, and a typical Amsterdam pub is located on almost every corner. Also in abundance are the Islamic butchers, Surinamese, Spanish, Indian and Turkish delicatessens and grocery stores.

It's easy to find your way in this area!

neighborhood_overview: Located on the Western Isles, three islands in the centre of Amsterdam, the Zoutkeetsgracht offers you a peaceful place to escape the energy of downtown Amsterdam. After the Second World War, the neighbourhood was rediscovered by various artists and has since then transformed into an appealing living- and working neighbourhood. The shipyards give the place a unique maritime atmosphere. Go for a walk alongside the impressive warehouses and be led towards a variety of trendy restaurants and unique shops that are part of the Western Isles.

neighborhood_overview:
Residences Old Centre is located on Amsterdam’s Westelijke Eilanden (western islands), a unique and quiet part of the city centre of Amsterdam.

The Westelijke Eilanden are three small islands in the city centre of Amsterdam. Together they form a pictorial, little neighbourhood with plenty of places where you’ll be surprised by its absolute beauty. This once old shipyard area is now a great place to stroll around and experience the best of the old parts of Amsterdam. Expect beautiful old warehouse buildings, small cafes, art galleries and a absolute local feeling in this magnificent downtown area. Although this area is in the city centre it has not been discovered by troops of tourist.

Hip places, green spaces and diverse faces. Ethnically diverse and strikingly spacious, Amsterdam East (Oost) is known for its wide streets lined by monumental 19th-century buildings, as well as its vibrant cultural mix. With plenty of opportunities for shopping, eating and drinking, the area boasts an exciting selection of trendy clubs, traditional Turkish bakeries, Surinamese supermarkets and Middle Eastern lunchrooms as well, of course, as the beautiful Oosterpark and the majestic Tropenmuseum.
In addition to plenty of parks, there are also quite a few places to visit and things to do. Have you been to Artis Zoo yet? In the summer Artis also hosts weekly concerts. be sure to also visit the world’s first microbe museum: Micropia. Or check out Amsterdam’s beautiful Hortus Botanicus, one of the oldest botanical gardens in the world.

host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

Now well-established as the hippest area of Amsterdam (and one of the priciest to live) de Pijp has everything that locals could crave. There’s the beautiful Sarphatipark, bustling Albert Cuypstraat market, and enough shops, bars, cafés and restaurants orbiting those to keep locals and visitors entertained for quite some time.

Originally built for Amsterdam’s workers during the 1800s to ease overpopulation in the Jordaan area, the neighbourhood has been re-purposed in the 21st Century by students, affluent singles and trendy young families who’ve settled in the area. With that, dozens of bars, cafés and boutiques have sprung up to service a population looking for good coffee and unique retail experiences.

But it’s the street market which still provides the heart and soul of the area. Held six days per week for over a century, it’s here, in the concentrated stream of grocery shoppers, that you’ll see a real slice of life with more locals (read ex-pats as well as Am

neighborhood_overview:
This apartment is located in Amsterdam Oost (East), an upcoming, vibrant district of Amsterdam. You won’t see many tourists here, because it’s the place where the locals love to hang when the city centre is too crowded. The apartment is just around the corner from the Linnaeusstraat: a buzzing street with many cool bars like the Biertuin and Kuijper. In the summer you’ll find the hippest Amsterdam crowd on sunny terraces, enjoying a “Brouwerij ‘t IJ’, a beer from the famous local brewery that’s located in a wind mill (also just 10 minutes away from the apartment). The Beukenplein is on the other side of the street; here you’ll find amongst others bars like Bar Bukowski (they serve great gin and tonics!), Maxwell and an amazing pizza place.

For very cheap, fresh food and a real Amsterdam experience you can walk your way up to the Dappermarkt, the multicultural market where locals buy their fruit and vegetables. Make sure to stop by the Oosterpark on the way, an amazing park

host_about:
How it all started...

On a historical dyke (former fisherman village), next to the IJsselmeer lake, in the typical Dutch rural landscape, but still very close to the unique city of Amsterdam.

As television producer I did (and do)  travel  a lot and I am always a fan of remarkable, unique accommodations to sleep and to stay in. Especially  excited do I get  when they are placed in the middle of nature or at unique locations.  Inspired by my visits to those spots, I decided to build my own little house, with all the comfort you need on a special place; my hometown Durgerdam/Amsterdam North.

Together with an architect we created the Tiny House. An authentic small wouden house, where I hope a lot of other people feel at home and can enjoy the green area & of course Amsterdam..

neighborhood_overview:
Spiegelkwartier

The Spiegelkwartier is the Art and Antiques district in Amsterdam.
Here you’ll find more than 70 antiques dealers and art galleries, together offering a resplendent array of fine historical objects, classic and contemporary art, and exotic folk art.
You will find also restaurants, casual eateries and cosy cafés on almost every corner.
The Spiegelkwartier is located between the Herengracht and the Rijksmuseum.

www.spiegelkwartier.nl

Museum Quarter

The Amsterdam Museum Quarter is home to the three most important museums in the Netherlands: the Rijksmuseum, the Stedelijk Museum and the Van Gogh Museum.
It also houses the majestic Concertgebouw and some superb cafés and restaurants.
With its large grassy open area, the Museumplein offers plenty of room to have a picnic or just relax. The Museum Quarter even has its own indoor swimming pool.
And a visit isn’t complete without posing with, or on, th

The Amsterdam forrest (Amsterdamse Bos) is three times the size of New York’s Central Park And entirely man-made. Spanning an impressive 1,000 hectares, the Amsterdamse Bos is among the largest city parks of Europe.
The Olympic stadium, the Olympic games of 1928 were held here and still hosting numerous sportive/cultural events.

I am a realtor since 20 years. Some of my hobbies are travelling,  Ibiza, (race) cycling, my work, cars, soccer and my close friends and family. 

We started this company 20 years ago. In April 2013 we started with renting out through Airbnb. With our experience in letting out to expats from the biggest Multinationals (Shell/Unilever/Johnson&Johnson) we know what people expect in a temporary apartment. 

We try to develop our apartments in a tasteful neutral style with high quality finishing and - furniture on nice locations like the Amsterdam Jordaan Area. Our apartments are not on the busiest places of Amsterdam but always on a maximum 3 minute walk from the canals. 

All our (Amsterdam)apartments are fully licensed by town hall what means that safety is on place 1. Infrared smoke detectors, flight plans, not too many people in 1 flat, no drugs etc.

We try to offer a hotel idea but than in an apartment. So more privacy, luxury, convenience and space on a AAA location but for a better price!

A definite no go is asking for a discount. If our prices are too high I would suggest to rent a bed where the owner was in the night before. 

Also we dont accept guests without any reviews. No exceptions. Sorry.


What is also convenient in our opinion is that we do not live our selves in the apartments. So You dont  sleep on a bed where someone has slept on for 5 years already. 

After every guest the apartments are professionally cleaned and so are  the towels and bedlinen by a professional company.

please see our reviews for confirmation if you are not convinced yet!

neighborhood_overview:
Home to some of the world’s best art museums, Oud-Zuid (Old-South) is one of Amsterdam’s most elegant and well-heeled neighbourhoods, where impressive manors line leafy streets, and chic boutiques abound. From the splendour of Museumplein to the vibrant Vondelpark and the serene boulevards of Willemspark, the beautiful neighbourhood of Oud-Zuid rewards the visitor at every turn.

Just outside the cultural heart of Amsterdam lies the posh neighbourhood of Oud-Zuid, with its ravishing villas and tranquil curving streets. The Oud-Zuid is arguably the elegant heart of Amsterdam, and is definitly the city’s most prestigious cultural district.

Amsterdam’s elegant Oud-Zuid (Old-South) was developed over a century ago as a cultural gateway to the city, at the tip of what was previously a boggy polder. It’s home to Rijksmuseum, Stedelijk Museum, and Van Gogh Museum – all of which exhibit the highlights of Western art. The nearby Vondelpark – created in the style of an Engl

We strive to offer you a pleasant and memorable stay in our home town: Amsterdam. We love to share the hidden gems with you, and we can provide you with all the information you need to get the most out of your stay. 

As we were awarded the 'superhost' status on airbnb, we can assure you that we will do our outmost to make your stay truly amazing. Please feel free to have a look at our 800+ reviews!

It has flexible and spacious social areas, filled with creative design touches like glass-fronted elevators, a light and airy café and an outdoor terrace. We’ve turned the former lecture hall into an impressive chill-out lounge and bar, while the old library is now a relaxation and private events room. The area has a varied mix of independent shops, old-school street markets, shiny new restaurants, traditional brown cafés and young expat and Amsterdammer families.

The modern and exciting, 14-hectare city park that surrounds the Westergasfabriek buildings is not only a perfect place to relax in natural surroundings, but also a venue for digital art and culture.

THE JORDAAN (a 10 minute walk)
The Jordaan is nothing but highlights. Maze-like streets offer hidden courtyards, cafes (both traditional and trendy), art galleries and pleasantly nosy neighbors. One also has access to some of the more scenic outdoor markets in the country. In particular, Noordermarkt has a flea market on Monday mornings and an organic farmers' market on Saturdays.

THE HAARLEMMERSTRAAT (a 15 minute walk)

neighborhood_overview:
The house is located in the Vondelpark-neighbourhood just between Oud Zuid and Oud West. The houses in this area were built at the end of 19th century. This part of Amsterdam has buildings like the Royal Concertgebouw, the Rijksmuseum, the Van Gogh museum and the Stedelijk Museum, all situated around the Museumplein. The city’s ‘green lung’ of Vondelpark remains Amsterdam’s most densely populated place-to-be whenever the sun shines. One can shop for everything from daily groceries to speciality chocolate; interior design items to beauty treatments.
In general the area is quiet and residential, but with nearby arterial streets providing easy access to daily shopping needs. It also features other children-friendly diversions such as parks and public swimming pools. Amsterdamse Bos (Amsterdam forest) is nearby for a quick nature escape.
The Vondelpark-neighbourhood is central: on one end you have Amsterdam’s nightlife and culture square Leidseplein and on the other Amstelveensew

The surrounding neighbourhood of bridge house Van Hallbrug offers an endless number of shopping, dining and sightseeing options that are worth a visit – all within walking or cycling distance. Just cross the bridge and you’ll find a small square with great places to get your morning coffee (Back to Black) or a delicious vegetarian meal (Vleesch noch Visch). Westerpark, the park where locals go for a festival or picnic, is at a 10-minute walk from the bridge house. Check out our self-composed Neighbourhood Guide on the tablet in the room for more recommendations!
host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

Amsterdam's District of Oost ('east') encompasses the areas of Plantage, Oosterparkbuurt, Indische buurt, Dapperbuurt and Amstel. Oost is strikingly green and spacious, yet it also has plenty of sights and opportunities for shopping, eating and drinking on offer.

For busy Amsterdam nightlife you can easily take the tram into the city centre but for a good meal and a pleasant evening out there is a great selection in our neighborhood which is home to some of the city's most highly-regarded restaurants: De Kas (who grow food in their own greenhouses), Merkelbach (slowfood in a park) and Riva (with beautiful views over the Amstel River).
In addition there are also a lot of smaller less expensive restaurants just around the corner.
host_about:
We are two graphic designers with our own studio in Amsterdam. We design books, photobooks posters and all sorts of print work. We also design exhibitions for musea at home and abroad. This house has been our family home for more than 20 years.

We know all about musea, galleries and cultural life in Amsterdam and will be very happy to advise on things for you to do and see during your stay. Some of the exhibitions have even been designed by us!

neighborhood_overview:
Our house is situated in a street that gives access to the Vondelpark, which is a treat in itself. This also opens up the possibility to walk to the museum district (The Modern Art Museum, Van Gogh Museum and the National Museum), a 15-minutes' walk from our house. Leidseplein, with its bars, cinemas and theatres is also a 15-minutes' walk from our house, although if it is pubs you are after, you may just as well grab a beer at Draft and Craft around the corner.
Our street gives access to the renowned and stately Vondelpark where you can have a drink and a chat either at the "Blauwe Theehuis" (Blue Tea House), the "Groot Melkhuis" (The Milkhouse) or the "Vondeltuin". Apart from that, you could also have a picnic at the park or just chill out. At the corner Overtoom - Kattenlaantje you could rent inline skates to make your way through the park in a sporty manner.
At Overtoom you can have your breakfast or lunch at Toasty (Overtoom 437) which can be found around the corner. A
host_about:
I am an academic who teaches English to seniors at two renowned private schools. I am into running, reading, and hot yoga. 
Six years ago, when our children had left the house, we started renting out their rooms for fun thinking that after one summer we would close shop. However, we still love hosting people from all walks of life and hope to be able to continue doing so.

I'm a freelance journalist living on my own, in this beautiful city. I love travelling, writing and trying to learn some surfing. I write mostly about health care, but like human interest stories too. Hope you'll have a wonderfull time in this amazing town!

neighborhood_overview:
For your on-shore entertainment the neighborhood offers the Javaplein with the Wilde Zwijnen restaurant, a Thai place, a FEBO and the Badhuis eat-cafe.
The fine restaurant Polder is also 5 bike-min away as is the Studio K club/cinema/barfood entertainment complex and a great many bars in the Javastraat.
Beerlovers head to Brouwerij t IJ proeflokaal also 5 bike minutes away.

My apartment is located in a lively neighbourhood, with many shops and restaurants in the nearby area. There is a nice mix of young professionals, families, students and expats living in this area. The main facilities are within walking distance.
host_about: Love travelling, fashion and meeting new people!

neighborhood_overview:

host_about:
Born in Copenhagen, architecture and design are my life. I regularly work with major Nordic design studios and during one of my trips I stopped off in Barcelona: I was captivated by its architecture, culture and Mediterranean colour. Such was the impact the city had on me that I decided to stay and carry on my latest project: Eric Vökel Boutique Apartments. 

Each of the apartments has been personally designed and decorated by me as if they might become my own home.

Welcome home!

Eric, 
Arquitect and designer

neighborhood_overview: There are many bars, restaurants and super markets within just a few minutes walk from our place. If you prefer something more busy you'll be in the neighbourhood 'De Pijp' in about 5 minutes by bike.
host_about:
We're a pretty mixed family and (depending on their mood) my three kids speak  French (my wife is French), Spanish (we just came back from living in Barcelona for 5 years) or Dutch to me. Keeps things interesting. 

We like traveling and stay at peoples homes is the best way of traveling for us.

neighborhood_overview:
2 min from Leidseplein, great central location for shops, transport, Vondelpark, nightlife but not noisy at night. Great for culture, work or play!

Leidseplein is the hotspot of Amsterdam, with hundreds of entertainment venues, live music from RocknRoll, Jazz, Electronic and more, comedy shows, clubs, bars, cocktails, restaurants, cinemas, you name it.

Beautiful Speigelstraat is 1 minute in the other direction, filled with art galleries, antiques, deli food, canals & bridges etc.

- 5 mins walk to Van Gogh museum, Stedelijk Modern Art, Rijksmuseum and Concert Hall
- 5 mins walk to Vondelpark
- 10 mins walk to Albert Cuyp market & The Heineken Experience
- 10 mins walk to Rembrandtplein and Dam Square
- 15 mins to Centraal Station
host_about:
I love live music, my work, balance, travel, the good life, being a host, not following, my friends and never ending family. Exploring and doing new things, give something back, everyone happy.

Favorite places and experiences: Amsterdam, Barcelona, eating freshly caught fish from a hammock in Goa, backpacking & scuba & skydiving & bungy in Oz, exploring overgrown ruins in the Cambodian jungle, picnic on the beach of remote uninhabited Scottish island, anywhere in Southeast Asia, anywhere new.

neighborhood_overview: The house is situated in a green residential area.
host_about: Grew up in Germany, studied in Berlin and France, travelled a bit, moved to the Netherlands, travelled a bit more, had kids, moved to the Caribbean for some time, travelled a bit more, now happy in Amsterdam

neighborhood_overview:
Child friendly quiet neighborhood in Amsterdam North, supermarkt oaroudn the corner, a canal to swim on walking distance. 5 minutes by bike to former shipyard and cultural hotspot NDSM, which hosts some nice restaurants, bars and art galleries and a monthly huge flea market. Many other restaurants, bars and shops on 10 minutes bike distance, many on the sunny side of the IJ-facing waterfront.
From NDSM take to ferry to be in Amsterdam center in 10 minutes.


Nature around the corner:
- In Amsterdam North you find the parks Noorderpark and Vliegenbos.
- The Twiske is an recreational nature area to the north, to reach by bike in 15 minutes. Within Het Twiske, you can rent canoes, rowboats, pedal boats and sailboat.
- The Waterland landscape is a scenic area located north of Amsterdam along the Markermeer (lake), 10 minutes by bike from our house. Here you'll find green meadows, grazing cows, colourful villages and traditional farmhouses.
- Explor
host_about: Hi, I'm Marieke, work as a strategic advisor for the city of Amsterdam. Philip is a creative director and artist. We have two sons (2 and 5) and live in Amsterdam.

neighborhood_overview: Bos en Lommer is een fijne rustige buurt, maar je bent binnen no-time bij de hoogtepunten van Amsterdam. De Jordaan en Oud-West zijn op 10 minuten afstand. Ook het Westerpark vind je op een paar minuten loopafstand.
host_about: Hoi, ik ben 25 jaar en woon nu sinds november 2018 met mijn vriend in ons heerlijke appartement. We verhuren het gedurende onze vakanties en hopen dat jullie er net zo van genieten als wij.

neighborhood_overview:
Living by the canal - that is a dream for many. In the past, however, this was considered frowned upon and not classical enough. Therefore the canal was filled up around 16th century. A beautiful park in the middle of the city was created - and still is today. Large trees that provide shade in summer and absorb the sounds of the city.
I love the Cafe Slijterij Oosterling (50m from us). Open since 1877, this is probably one of the most authentic places in Amsterdam. Time seems to stand still here. If you are hungry, you can get delicious sandwiches, burgers, salads or freshly caught fish in the Brasserie Nel (400m). If you prefer self-catering and our shared kitchen, the supermarket is only 70m away.

host_about: We are a French-Russian family living and working in Amsterdam, The Netherlands. We love the place where we live, surrounded by birds and trees, full of the hundreds of books we have collected for many years.

neighborhood_overview: Nieuwe Markt
host_about: Airplanes and cats :-)

neighborhood_overview: The penthouse offers panoramic views on the city, including direct view on Dam Square and the Royal Palace. Located right between the shopping street Nieuwendijk, The Royal Palace on Dam Square and the famous gothic church called Nieuwe Kerk.

The unique selling point of the studio is the location in 'De Pijp', offering best of both worlds: The Pijp is the most central neighbourhood of all Amsterdam, providing all the convenience of having everything close-by. But, without being a complete tourist zone, so you can still relax or stay comfortable at home.

The studio is located in the neighborhood 'De Pijp', a historical neighbourhood for local residents reflecting that all kinds of cultures and backgrounds can live together, side by side. Too much to tell about, but for now on a short notice:

It's alive, vibrant and contains a socially beautiful mix of students, young professionals, traditional 'Amsterdammers' and social housing for the elderly. You can take a stroll for hours and you won't stop noticing terraces to enjoy, any culture & kitchen imaginable, cosy city parks, shops, canals and traditional & trendy café's.

Look into the lovely Sarphati city park, the famous Albert Cuypmarket and
host_about: Positive and easy-minded Psychologist - enjoy life! A happy member of the AIRBNB-community: I love to host guests in my own house in Amsterdam, and I love to travel the world! Always looking forward to meet people!

neighborhood_overview: At 5 minutes from the boat you will find the beautiful and lively neighbourhood called Nieuwmarkt. There is a market on saturdays. There are many restaurants, terraces, Chinese supermarkets etc.

One of the best area from Amsterdam, Amsterdam Oud Zuid is very close to Museumplein but just outside the touristic chaos. Best shops and restaurants are around, the neighborhood is very safe and green! Easy to bike around and to the city centre.
host_about: Serial entrepreneur - In love with Innovation - Inspired by young generation

host_about: Mijn naam is Yoka en ik woon samen met mijn partner in de mooie stad Amsterdam.  Ik ben  psychiatrisch verpleegkundige en werkzaam als ZZPer in diverse ziekenhuizen rondom Amsterdam. Daarbij run ik samen met mijn partner Taira de GoldenGuel B&B. Dit doen we met veel plezier. Ik hou van muziek/films/dans en reizen.

neighborhood_overview: I love the fact that I live in the middle of the center but it still feels like a little quiet corner of the city: beautiful views, the water and the nice little restaurants and bars at the corner.
host_about: I love to travel, meet the locals and have been all over the world already! I rent my accommodation in Amsterdam while I am away. Cities and countries on my 'to visit' list: Berlin, Barcelona, Lissabon, Australia, Indonesia. :)

neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood is very friendly with many things to explore. There is a park nearby so you can take your kids to play.
The area is also very central where as mentioned before you can get anything around! Other than being central, it is a very quiet and calm neighborhood where I am sure you will enjoy the most out of it!

The Two side view: green from the tree in the back, in the front the terraces of the Maasstraat so you can enjoy of both views.

The house is situated in the middle of "Old South", a popular neighbourhood just South of Amsterdam’s city center. The area counts numerous of charming restaurants, (secondhand) shops, and is home to some of Amsterdams famous museums such as Rijksmuseum, Van Gogh Museum and Stedelijk Museum. The street itself is very lively (tram 2). Also nearby the famous Cornelis Schuyt, P.C. Hooftstraat, and Vondelpark where you can do a lot of outdoor sports like jogging, skating, walking, cycling. With tram 2 it is only a few minutes away to the picturesque and famous canals.
host_about:
Ik kom uit Amsterdam en woon samen met mijn vriend. Ben opgeleid als juriste maar op dit moment met veel plezier werkzaam in de interieurbranche!
Hobbies, koken lezen reizen sporten; tennis hardlopen

Hi! I am Debby, together with Frits and our 3 kids (16, 14 and 11 years old) we enjoy living in the heart of vibrant Amsterdam.  We have completely renovated our 1890's house and daily enjoy living in it! I was born and raised in France and look forward to welcome guests in our house.

neighborhood_overview: Besides the park and market, our neighbourhood offers a lot of bars, good quality restaurants, (organic) grocery stores and boutiques within walking distance from the apartment. It is one of the most multi ethnic neighbourhoods in the city centre of Amsterdam.

The apartment is located in the West of Amsterdam, next to the beginning of the "Admiraal de Ruijterweg" in the nicest part of " De Baarsjes" neighborhood. A gentrified and upcoming neighborhood. There are a lot of nice shops, restaurants and bars around. Within a 2-minute walking radius Restaurants: Fam. Speijkervet, Bar Spek, Faam. Supermarkets and shops: Albert Heijn, Aldi en Stach (hip bio minimarket literally around my corner). Some steps further (5 min) on the De Clercqstraat there are the bars and restaurants: Pazzo, Fier, De Rotisserie, Hendrix, Kip aan het Spit, La Cantina. Last but not least " de Hallen: this is a culinairy complex in an old tram depot. Taste various cuisines and top your evening of with a visit to the cinema in this complex.
host_about: Hi, my name is Johanna. I have been living in Amsterdam since 2004, with some minor interruptions. I am on airbnb to experience other places through a more local point of view and hope to offer people the same experience in my home town. I am curious and outgoing,  interested in arts, design, international relations and enjoy interacting with people from other countries and cultures.

neighborhood_overview: So central you can walk to everything, although I prefer the bike myself.
host_about: Are you interested in making a booking - short term or long-term? We're happy to offer a comfortable apartment for your stay in Amsterdam.

neighborhood_overview:
THE NEIGHBORHOOD:

We are in the city centre in a quiet neighbourhood (Helmersbuurt). The neighbourhood is very popular and known for its nice bars, restaurants and plenty of facilities for families with children. Recently new (coffee) bars have been opened around the corner and across the street is one of the best bakeries in Amsterdam; 't Vlaams Broodhuys.

We are in walking distance from the Vondelpark (famous its quiet places, great terraces and free concerts) with and many other attractions such as the museum square, Leidse Square, Jordaan, the famous 'negen straatjes' and pop venue Paradiso. The high class PC Hooftstraat shopping street is also in walking distance.

Paid parking space is widely available in our street. There are several supermarkets (discount, organic and 'normal') in our area, all within a three minutes walk. You can take a 10 min bike ride (or just one of the trams close to our home) to the Albert Cuip Market or the Dam Square and
host_about:
I am a mom of three and a web designer. We love living in the city in our  spacious and cosy home in the middle of the city. I can't live without my family, friends, music, my IPhone and my home town Amsterdam. 

My style of travelling is 'live like the locals do' - try to get off the beaten track by just walking around town or asking advice to local people in a bar or grocery store. I love to make myself at home and offer the possibilities for other people to do the same when they visit me. Oh, and I am crazy about lighthouses...

neighborhood_overview: The street is very cozy and quite. There are no cars and not a lot of tourists. If you walk out of the street to the Herengracht or Single you arrive in the middle of the city.

This is an area filled with people who left the city center because it was too crowded and the houses to small, but did'nt want to go too far. Kids have a lot of space and feel free. Everything is on walking distance: the beach, the small harbor, the restaurants and bars surrounding it, supermarkets, tram and bus. The tram takes only 15 minutes to Central Station, by bike it takes half an hour to the east part of Amsterdam.
host_about: We've built our house ourselves. We love to share our house with nice people when we are on vacation. We enjoy the holiday feeling of this area, we swim and surf in the sea or in the canal behind the house. We love not to be in the busy citycenter but can choose to go there whenever we feel like it. Its even possible to bike to the center and the tram takes only 15 min to central. In warm and cold weather the view is astonishing because of the clouds and the sea. This is a perfect familyhouse

neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood is very peaceful, safe and family-friendly. It has a bit of a village vibe inside a bigger city. The direct neighborhood is considered upscale, with lots of families with children living in the area.

There is a playground directly around the corner, with a picnic area and the possibility to swim in the dock during summer.

There is also a traditional Dutch snackbar (Febo), and a bike rental (Halfords) just around the corner and an outisde neighborhood (farmers') market every Wednesday, Friday and Saturday, called 'Pekmarkt'.

The market, and closest supermarket, grocery shops and stores are located at Mosveld, a 10-15 minute walk or a 3-4 minute bike ride.
The opening hours from the supermarket (Albert Heijn) are 7-22 and 8-22 during the weekend, also on Sunday!

It is very easy to get to the house from the Central Station.

Once you cross the IJ canal, it is 10-15 minute walk or 4 minute bike ride to the loca
host_about:
Hi! We are Eva & Kobe.  

You’re more than welcome to stay at one of the fabulous apartments and homes we manage while the home owners are on holiday. 

We like to think we offer the best of both worlds: you can enjoy a one-of-a-kind vacation experience in a unique property, without compromising on service and convenience.

We strive to offer you a pleasant and memorable stay in our home town: Amsterdam. We love to share the hidden gems with you, and we can provide you with all the information you need to get the most out of your stay. 

As we were awarded the 'superhost' status on airbnb, we can assure you that we will do our outmost to make your stay truly amazing. Please feel free to have a look at our 800+ reviews!

Our core values are similar to the ones on which airbnb is founded, hospitality & live like a local is what's is all about. We are flexible, always available and will welcome you in person, show you around and answer all of your questions.  Exceptions with us offering a self check-in can be made during 2020.

Combined with the fact that our standards of cleanliness are very high, you can certainly expect our properties to be 100% clean. All our high quality bath- and bed linen are professionally cleaned and ironed.  

Please feel free to contact us if you have any questions or special requests. We'll be happy to assist you! We would be delighted to host you during your stay in Amsterdam!

neighborhood_overview: The neighbourhood is characterized by its location on the edges of the Center, Oud-Zuid and Oud-West and offers the best of these three worlds: the Leidseplein and the Jordaan within walking distance, the Vondelpark and  multiple bars and quality restaurants. Despite all these nice places in the immediate vicinity, it is still a quiet and very safe neighbourhood. In short, the liveliness of the Center, the allure of Oud Zuid and the intimacy of Oud West united!

Welcome to my house boat, located in the rapidly upcoming popular Amsterdam Noord area, just north of central station. A 15 minute walk (or 5 minute bike ride) from the Amsterdam tower, Central Station and the NDSM area. Surrounded by popular gems like "de Ceuvel", restaurant "de klaproos", Cinema "FC Hyena", "Monk"climbing hall, the "Van der Pek" street market, there is a lot of interesting stuff going on in the area. And yet, this floating sustainably built village is an oasis of tranquility in Amsterdam. Developed and built by its inhabitants these 30 houseboats form Europe's most sustainable floating neighborhood are home to 46 families in a tight knit community. Go for a swim outside, take the kayak for a ride, take a stroll in nearby Noorderpark, or take the bike up to the country side not far away.
host_about: I'm a filmmaker from amsterdam. I like arts, restaurants, travelling, concerts. I am also the founding father of this sustainable floating community called ‘Schoonschip’ in Amsterdam.

neighborhood_overview:
The beautiful Rembrandtpark is right next to the apartment on a 1-minute walk. Bars and restaurants are within a few minutes' walking distances; Zurich, Biertuin (biergarden), Bar Baarsch, and Cook.
Breakfast and coffee at espresso bar Buongiorno or White Label Coffee. Also within a walking distance are the supermarkets, night shops, coffee shop and a sports center with swimming pool.
The neiberhood is great, very lively, Shops, supermarkets, nice lunch places all within walking distance.  This vibrant area is one of the nicest in Amsterdam!

Old West also known as the Golden west area is a neighborhood known for its nice restaurants, bars, terraces, and shops. Walking distance from the Vondelpark.
The well-known museums and shopping street PC Hooftstraat is reachable within 10 minutes walk.

host_about:
I am a retired Montessori teacher, living in the same house as the apartment is situated. We rent this place for 24 years with so much pleasure. 
My husband is a pediatric surgeon.
The three kids left University and live in Amsterdam.
We rent the apartment for over 22 years. A lot of guests return and love to live like a local.

neighborhood_overview: The villa is located at the most beautiful location of IJ-burg and therefore called, IJ-biza . IJburg Is a new part of Amsterdam, build in the IJsselmeer a large lake. If you like watersports, this is the place to be. The surf school and marina are just around the corner. If you bring your own boat, you can park it in front of the watervilla
host_about: I am a born Amsterdammer and love to give tourists a truely unique Amsterdam Experience. With my boat we can organize a private boat tour through the cannels or sail to Amsterdam-Castle.

neighborhood_overview: The house is within walking distance of the new metro station. The metro will take you in several minutes to different places at the city center of Ammsterdam. It is also near the country site where you can see the beautiful old villages of Holland. It is also near the Zaanse Schans an area with historic wooden buildings and a lot of windmills that still work.

The neighborhoud our apartment is really unique. As it is located in is in a very quiet area of Amsterdam, it is still extremely close to the popular Jordaan area and beautiful Westerpark. There are a lot good restaurants, cafés, bars and coffee places within walking distance of the apartment. Please see our map for our guide for our personal favourites.
host_about:
Hello! 

My name is Sophie and I've been living in Amsterdam for the past 8 years. My boyfriend Tim and I bought our beautiful apartment 3 years ago. 

We've put a lot of effort into make our apartment into a place of peace and comfort. Tim is a designer and has decorated the interior beautifully. 

With my love of plants and gardening I have created a lush green rooftop garden on the balcony and roof terrace. 

The large amount of space, natural light and greenery makes this my favourite place on earth. It allows me to relax completely and forget about everything when I get home from a stressful day at work. 

We would love to share our lovely home with you!
I am a young working professional in the Tech industry; Hoping to find guests that will treat my home as their own! Feel free to reach out if interested in my listing

neighborhood_overview: The Flevopark is right outside the apartment, and the lively Javastraat is 8 min walking where you can find some the locals favorite restaurants and bars. For the city centre you can take Tram 3 or 14 to be there in 20 min.
Literally next to the Vondelpark and the vibrant J.P. Heijestraat but with the benefits of a calm and quiet street.

The Eastern Docklands are a true example of the architectural vitality of Amsterdam. YAYS Amsterdam Docklands is located on the Cruquiuseland. Here you'll experience the life of a local. The area used to be an extension of the port of Amsterdam. Nowadays it is an up and coming district being redeveloped.
host_about:
YAYS Group is an established serviced apartment provider managing 15 aparthotels in Amsterdam, The Hague, the Paris metropolitan area, and Antwerp under the lifestyle brands YAYS (fully serviced aparthotels) and by YAYS (serviced apartments with partially self-serviced solutions). 
Each of the 500 YAYS Group apartments is stylish, spacious, fully equipped, and located in a convenient area. A YAYS Group serviced apartment is a home away from home that sets you on the inside track to local living.

#unlocktheneighbourhood

neighborhood_overview: Within walking distance you find a supermarket, a backery, a butcher, several restaurants, harbour, a city beach and several parks.
host_about: Family man, love being on the water waterskiing, swimming. Furthermore entrepeneur and businessman.

neighborhood_overview:
It is a popular neighbourhood
Safe, spacious and a lot to see
Close to the centre but very quiet

The area is next to the second biggest park in Amsterdam, you can relax in the sun here, go for a run in the mornings. There are local food markets, festivals, art movie house, galleries,  restaurants and  breakfast/ lunch spots. The apartment is situated 10 minutes from the Jordaan , with unique clothing and interior stores and pubs.
host_about: I work for a startup accelerator specialised in sustainability.  Living in the upcoming creative part of Amsterdam with a great mixture of culture, food, entrepreneurs in the creative field, markets, summerfestivals and a great park. Working and free time blend together here. I enjoy to open my house to anyone who likes to explore Amsterdam.

neighborhood_overview: Quiet neighborhood. Supermarkets right outside the door. Hoofddorpplein is a nice area with a lot of bars and restaurants. Tram 2 takes you right into the city centre.
host_about: I am an assistant professor in Clinical Psychology and licensed psychologist at Leiden University. Currently I am living in Amsterdam, which I really enjoy. In my spare time I like to be active in multiple sports, visit musea, meet up with friends and join the occasional party. Of course I like to travel using Airbnb and meet up with new people!

neighborhood_overview:
We love to live in this part of Amsterdam; you'll find restaurants, bakeries, a supermarket, flower stall etc. around the corner but it isn't crowded like the city center. And still: tram and bus will take you to the city center in only 15 minutes.

Many outdoor play options (playgrounds) for children a stone's throw away: at the back of our house, Mariotteplein, Jeugdland, ARTIS zoo.

Nice restaurants, bars etc: bar 1900, Pizza Beppe, restaurant de Kas, Café Cliché, la Vallade, Polder, de Vergulden Eenhoorn, de Pizzabakkers.
host_about: Hi! I am Charlotte. We are a family of five, living and working in the best city of the Netherlands: Amsterdam. I am working for an international children’s rights NGO and my husband works in the wine and champagne business.

neighborhood_overview: The apartment is located in a very calm (unesco listed) street, 1 minute walking from the Vondelpark, 5 minutes walking from the museum square and 5 minutes walking from the canals and the leidseplein. 10 minutes walking from the foodhallen. Anything is around the corner and everything is on a walkable distance.
host_about: I'm a Dutch documentary maker, born and raised in  Amsterdam, living half of the time in Rio de Janeiro and travelling the world for filmmaking. Currently I'm living in Kenya working on film projects. When I'm not in Amsterdam, I'm renting out my apartment.
property_type: Private room in bed and breakfast

neighborhood_overview:
Our home in located the picturesque district 'Elzenhagen', with houses build in a very typical Dutch Zaanse style. It is perfectly located, with close by on the one hand central Amsterdam and on the other Waterland, the typical Dutch countryside. The charming villages and tranquil surroundings of neighbouring Waterland region make it a perfect destination for exploring by bike.

We will lay out two lists for you. One with our favorite places to visit in the center of lovely Amsterdam and one with our favorite spots in Amsterdam-North, the 7th most hip neighborhoods of the world, according to (URL HIDDEN)
"Amsterdam North has an industrial feel and became one of the coolest neighbourhoods over the last years. More and more hotspots are popping up!"

neighborhood_overview: Traditionally a blue collar neighbourhood just a stone's throw away from the heart of town, 'De Baarsjes', is what one calls 'on the rise'. All around us we see new initiatives popping up; from intimate coffee bars and restaurants, to cool boutiques with local designers. Please ask the staff for inside info on where to go!
host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel is a place in Amsterdam where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

neighborhood_overview:
The Groenburgwal is a canal in Amsterdam that connects the Raamgracht with the Amstel. The Groenburgwal is parallel to the Kloveniersburgwal and the Zwanenburgwal, in the shadow of the tower of the Zuiderkerk.

The area between the Kloveniersburgwal and the Zwanenburgwal was until late in the 16th century "the site outside the fortress at the Amstel". In 1593 the area was added to the city.

Cloth weavers worked here. The wool was washed, carded and spun, then cloth was woven from it. After fulling and dyeing the cloth was tensioned on wooden frames to dry and stretch. The names of the nearby Raamgracht, the Raamsloot near Rusland, dug in 1537, and the Verversstraat (1593) recall those activities.

In the early 17th century, the Amstel between Kloveniersburgwal and Groenburgwal and a little later the 's Gravelandse Veer, between Groenburgwal and Blauwbrug, was compressed. Around that time the name Groenburgwal was born; green dyers were specially establish

Originally it was a working-class neighbourhood, but the Jordaan is now one of the most expensive and upscale locations to live in the Netherlands. Many art galleries, particular for modern art, speciality shops, restaurants, traditional cafes, and markets characterize this romantic and historical part of Amsterdam.

In the Jordaan there are many sights worth seeing such as the Westertoren, the impressive Anne Frank House, the Houseboat Museum, the Pianola Museum and did you know that the famous Dutch painter Rembrandt

neighborhood_overview:
The boat is moored at the Amstel River, the main canal of Amsterdam, on the edge of the Pijp neighborhood, one of the most cosmopolitan and vibrant districts of Amsterdam. You will find bars, restaurants, shops, the Albert Cuijp market and public transport around you at walking distance. Most places offer take-away food or food-on-order in case of a lock down.

A nice 15 to 20 minute walk along the Amstel River brings you to the central canal area and the major nightlife area Rembrandtplein, Hermitage Museum or Waterlooplein Flee market.

The boat is also a great starting point for exploring Amsterdam and its surroundings by boat or bike, for example to Ouderkerk aan de Amstel or Weesp. By car it takes half an hour to reach the North sea beach, the forests near Hilversum or the welcoming lakes of Loosdrecht.
host_about:
It was always a dream to live on a houseboat. 

I like to share this wonderful experience with people from all over the world.

neighborhood_overview: My apartment is in one of the nicest parts of the city. It's close to the city center and the most known squares like Leidsesquare and Museumsquare (10 min walk). In 5 minutes you'll be in the Vondelpark where you can stroll around and have a coffee. The big shopping street around the corner (Kinkerstraat) has all you need and there are several supermarkets close by. You'll be staying in Old West, with its many restaurants and bars and they recently opened 'the Hallen', which has a great foodmarket and bars. I really love this part of town and I am sure you will too.

So the theme seems to continue to inspire me for the last 20 years. Hope to meet you one day! All the best, Melle

neighborhood_overview: We love living here because we can go to the city centre whenever we want (catch a movie, go shopping or visit one of the many museums). The neighborhood is very friendly. Our kids can play outside freely an safe.

We have a garden with table and gardenseats. In front of our house is a common garden or rather a play field where all neighbourhoodkids ( 0 - 12 years) meet. There are hardly any cars in our street so ever one runs in and out freely.


If you come by car, the parking in our neighbourhood during the day is with a blue clock system. You can set for a few hours, so it won’t be to expensive. Before 9.00 and after 19.00, there’s no blue clock system. A blue clock card is available for you.

Traditionally a blue collar neighbourhood just a stone's throw away from the heart of town, 'De Baarsjes', is what one calls 'on the rise'. All around us we see new initiatives popping up; from intimate coffee bars and restaurants, to cool boutiques with local designers. Please ask the staff for inside info on where to go!
host_about:
Hotel Not Hotel is a place in Amsterdam where a room isn’t just a room, but a work of art with its own creator, story, and identity. Most of them designed and specially made by Collaboration-O, a group of young designers that originated from the Eindhoven Design Academy, and one by Arno Coenen and his partner IRIS.

When you wake up, you step into an art-filled, exhibition-like space instead of an anonymous lobby or hallway. The entire hotel is one big living room, with cosy seating areas between the cottages. Combined with our luxury beds and other facilities, Hotel Not Hotel offers an unrivalled experience. 
Besides all this, we feel that the value of a city lies in experiencing its local day-to-day life. As we are closely connected to Amsterdam and its numerous creative entrepreneurs, we know where to send you for a night on the town, a hidden culinary gem, or an upcoming artist’s exhibition. 

The bar connected to Hotel Not Hotel is called Kevin Bacon. Just like the actor, the bar has zero pretention, it always delivers, and it makes sure everybody has a good time.

Kevin Bacon is not your typical hotel bar. It’s where locals get their morning coffee or a quick breakfast. It’s where friends meet for a cocktail or a beer before diving into the nightlife, and where hotel guests let their hair down after a long day in the city.

When the weather is good, the ‘Whitey the White’ terrace is sunny like a perfectly fried egg. The staff’s friendly attitude shines all year round.

Its also on the border of the South Amsterdam, the Soho called the PIJP.
Amsterdam East, or simply Oost (pronounced ‘oast'), is an incredibly diverse district of Amsterdam that encompasses neighbourhoods that couldn't be more different from one another. Dapperbuurt hosts a huge market on one of the few streets in the region not named after an Indonesian island and is the ideal locale to try a Moroccan cookie or a real Turkish kebab.
Finally, a trip to Oost wouldn't be complete without a visit to one of the trendy cafés on Linnaeusstraat by the Oosterpark and Beukenplein (around the corner) for the best coffee, cocktails and ice-cream!

During the 'Golden Century', a gold bank stood right at the center of Amsterdam. Behind this bank once was an alley. After the Tulip-boom the bank went bankrupt and had to break up the land the alley once was and sold it separately. At one side a little house was erected with room for a small shop at the ground floor and tree floors of living space on top. For over a century it was used in this way. But, after refurbishing it to today standards, the two top floors are now available for rent!

Located 5 min from: Dam, Anne Frank House, Jordan Area, Red Light District, 9 streets, trams to all directions.

Centrally located though, close to Schiphol Airport and minutes away from the cities main attractions (by tram, walking or cycling): the famous Vondel Park, Museum District, Anne Frank Museum, Concert Gebouw etc, restaurants, bike hire, pubs, main shopping districts, popular fruit & vegetable market (Ten Kate market) and the main entertainment districts. There is a Tram stop literally around the corner.
Enjoy the eclectic mix of Oud-West at the district's most popular terraces, known for good drinks and reasonably-priced food. If you are the sporty type you can also go for a run in the Vondelpark or just lay on the grass and enjoy the greenery - perfect for people watching.
Tram 1 is very close to the apartment. It will connect you to anywhere you would like to go. For example, the Anna Frank house is only 10min while Schiphol airport is on

neighborhood_overview:
Rivierenbuurt is a neighbourhood of Amsterdam, Netherlands. The neighbourhood is situated in the eastern part of the borough of Amsterdam-Zuid, bordered by the river Amstel to the east, the Boerenwetering canal in the west, the Amstelkanaal in the north and the A10 motorway in the south. In 2013, the Rivierenbuurt had approximately 28,400 residents.[1]

The Rivierenbuurt was built in the 1920s as a primarily middle-class residential area, part of the Plan Zuid urban expansion programme designed by Dutch architect Hendrik Petrus Berlage.[2] The neighbourhood features many fine examples of Amsterdam School architecture. The Dutch word Rivierenbuurt translates as 'Rivers Neighbourhood', which refers to the fact that most streets in the area are named after rivers in the Netherlands.

Until World War II the area had a sizable Jewish population[3] which included Anne Frank and her family, who lived at Merwedeplein square until they went into hiding in the secret annex lo

Just around the corner (2 to 5 minutes walking) are many nice bars and restaurants.

Have breakfast at Bagels & Beans at 2 minutes walk from the houseboat. Lunch at my personal favorite "De Hoftuin" located at the backside of the Hermitage museum, or take your lunch-to-go and eat it in the secret garden of the Royal Zoo Artis (5 minutes walk).

Have diner around the corner in restaurant "Aguada", or in "De Plantage" located in one of the old buildings of the Royal Zoo. Or try "Nel" at the other side of the river Amstel, in a white wooden former church on a lovely square underneath large chestnut trees! Visit an authentic bar like Eik en Linde (4 minutes walk) or Krom (10 minutes)

The metro is at 3 minutes walking. Which will take you to central station in 4 minutes. You can use all the metro lines, so they arrive within minutes.

Also, if you take the metro, you're at Nieuwmarkt square within 6 minutes (including the walk!), where you'll find

Kinkerstraat is a multicultural area with a large shopping street filled with bars, restaurants, clothes etc. It’s criss-crossed with commercial streets, including Overtoom which has become a major interiors boulevard. Two of the city’s more interesting alternative cultural complexes, OT301 and Lab111, which both mix music, film and art, are located here. neighborhood_overview:
The Amsterdam Canal District is a neighborhood in Amsterdam, Netherlands. The seventeenth-century canals of Amsterdam, located in the center of Amsterdam, were added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in August 2010. The Amsterdam Canal District consists of the area around the city’s four main canals: Singel, Herengracht, Keizersgracht, and Prinsengracht. From Brouwersgracht, the canals are generally parallel with one another, leading gradually southeast into the Amstel river.

Many of the canal houses in the Amsterdam Canal District are from the Dutch Golden Age in the 18th century. Many of these buildings, however, underwent restoration or reconstruction in various centuries, meaning that these building display many different architectural styles and facades.

neighborhood_overview:
Schellingwoude is a former Fishing-village in the Northern part of Amsterdam. The Monumental Dike is situated between meadows, park and the IJ, with the City Centre just at the other side of the water. Various (sustainable/organic) grocery stores, supermarkets and bakeries are at walking distance.

A perfect area for cycling, Marken and Volendam are a 30 minute bike-ride along the dike, Edam and Monnikendam are at the distance of an hour by bike through beautiful meadows with horses, cows and sheep. One can have a break or High Tea in one of the authentic Cafes or a glass of biological milk, or biological ice-cream in a farm on the way. Excellent (sustainable) restaurants in both the rural countryside and in the artistic part of Northern Amsterdam - De Ceuvel, Pllek, Il Pecorino, Wilhelmina Dok (with views on the large cruiseships), Loetje, De Goudfazant, etc. Or one can have a cool beer or white wine on a terrace at Het Sluisje, Het Schoolhuis, Beer Brewery Oedipus, Landmark

neighborhood_overview:
The modest origins of the Jordaan (it was built to house Jewish and French immigrant workers) is still visible in its small, very old houses and the fact there is an old cafe on nearly every corner (often the type where locals will burst into folk music on Sunday drinking sessions). Nowadays these old brown cafes share space with brick oven pizzerias, boutique design shops and other trappings of the young professional set.
Nice to know: each of the streets is named after a flower.

This house is located in the middle of the popular Jordaan, a side street from Lindengracht. Partially residential, partially lively with many restaurants and bars. But not the noisy type of nightlife ☺
A 1 minute walk brings you to the most photographed site of Amsterdam, the corner of Brouwersgracht and Prinsengracht. It doesn’t get any prettier.
Do you need more buzz? Go to the dazzling Haarlemmerstraat full of restaurants, deli’s, and one-of-a-kind shops. Parallel you find the Brouwersgracht, to some (at least to us) the prettiest of all Amsterdam canals.
The Jordaan is an excellent place to spend your mornings and evenings, and discover the major attractions during the day. The main museums are all within 10 minute biking distance. The popular 'Anne Frank' House is in the Jordaan, about a 10 minutes walk away. Just a bit further from the Anne Frank house you reach the '9 straatjes' (9 streets) district. This area is known for its unique shops, boutiques and cozy

neighborhood_overview:
If you want to be right next to the buzz, but still have a quiet sleep at night this is the place for you! De Pijp is one of the most popular areas of the city because of its lively character and accessibility.
The apartment is located in a quiet street but just around the corner from all the bars and restaurants, the beautiful Sarphatipark and the famous Albert Cuyp market. Also the Heineken brewery, Museumplein (with all museums) and Vondelpark are within walking distance.

Within minutes of walking in the other direction you enter De Jordaan, originally a working-class neighbourhood, but now the most famous area of Amsterdam. Its heart is formed by what is known to locals as ‘The Nine Streets’. These small and charming streets are overflowing with vintage and designer shops, specialty stores, art galleries, cosy cafés and great little restaurants of almost every kind you can think of. Walking through these streets you will hear the bells of the Westertoren – the same ones Anne Frank described in her diary, while in hiding during the Second World War. Visiting the world famous Anne Frank House, now a biographical museum, offers an unforgettable experience.

Many houses in De Jordaan have inner courtyards, built by rich people for elderly women, which are lovely to visit. There are three markets; one at the Westerstraat, one at the Lindengracht and last but not least: De Noordermarkt, the oldest and most beautiful organic farmer’s market, everyon

If you'd like to go out at night there are several bars and lounges in this neighborhood. On a ten minute walk you find Club Air and Club Abe, which are two popular big clubs.

The farmhouse is located in a green area of Amsterdam. On the west and east side there are small fields with my goats and sheep. North is the Haarlemmerweg, the exit road to Amsterdam, Haarlem, Alkmaar and The Hague. The nature reserve "De Bretten" is also to the north. To the south is the sports park where you can play tennis and there are annual rugby matches held at a global level. De Farmhouse is located in  "Tuinen van West" nature and recreation area. This area is located in a regional greenstructure and is therefore particularly animal and plant species rich. In the Tuinen van West there are various restaurants and accesable fruit and vegetable growers as well as an organic supermarket. The recreation area is connected with various surrounding nature and recreational areas such as Spaarnwoude and Het Amstelland. From here you can cycle out of the city into the green. If you want more Nature then a trip to the North Holland dune area is recommended or to the Oostvaardersplassen.

The ship is moored in the Jordaan, bordering the ‘9 little streets’ area. You could say this is Amsterdam’s Greenwich Village, home to many art galleries, narrow alleys, leafy canals lined with 17th-century houses, quirky specialty shops, cafes, designer boutiques and restaurants. The central Leidseplein, the Anne Frank Museum and the Dam are all a 10-minute walk. Your view over the Prinsengracht canal is towards the Westerkerk.

The Rembrandt house is right around the corner and the Anne Frank house is at a stone’s throw away. The city centre is the most historic part of Amsterdam, so you will be surrounded by the famous Amsterdam canals and the typical houses lined along them. The iconic architecture, decorative lights and bridges make the city centre the most romantic part of the city.

neighborhood_overview: Houthaven is a neighbourhood of Amsterdam, Netherlands situated in the West borough. It is currently predominantly used by inland barges, however plans are in motion to radically change the area in the next few years by building a new residential area on seven artificial islands.

Spiegelkwartier

The Spiegelkwartier is the Art and Antiques district in Amsterdam.
Here you’ll find more than 70 antiques dealers and art galleries, together offering a resplendent array of fine historical objects, classic and contemporary art, and exotic folk art.
You will find also restaurants, casual eateries and cosy cafés on almost every corner.
The Spiegelkwartier is located between the Herengracht and the Rijksmuseum.

www.spiegelkwartier.nl

Museum Quarter

The Amsterdam Museum Quarter is home to the three most important museums in the Netherlands: the Rijksmuseum, the Stedelijk Museum and the Van Gogh Museum.
It also houses the majestic Concertgebouw and some superb cafés and restaurants.
With its large grassy open area, the Museumplein offers plenty of room to have a picnic or just relax. The Museum Quarter even has its own indoor swimming pool.
And a visit isn’t complete without posing with, or on, th

neighborhood_overview: If the sun is out you should definitely go to Rembrandtpark or Vondelpark. There are plenty of nice restaurants nearby. I'm happy to give you tips for your stay!

The convenient located apartments are close to the Central Station and right in de middle of the oldest part of Amsterdam. In the close vicinity numerous museums can be found like the Rembrandt House, the National Maritime Museum and Nemo Science Museum. The old city zoo Artis is also close by. The famous Nieuwmarkt, China Town, Waterloopplein and Dam Square are only a few minutes away.

There is a big park nearby (Flevopark) you are allowed to barbeque there if you like. There are many sportfields and several shops (supermarket AH, liquor store, greengrocer, bakery, fitness, hairdresser, bank, toy store, fishmonger, drugstore etc.) quite near. Just a 5 minute walk.

The Jordaan is a famous district in the center of Amsterdam. Originally it was a working-class neighborhood, but now the Jordaan is one of the most expensive locations in Amsterdam. Most of the streets and canals are named after flowers and trees. It is a cosy neighborhood with many traditional cafes, art galleries, modern art and specialty shops and restaurants. Many houses have inner courtyards, the courtyards were built by rich people for elderly women. There are 3 markets in this district; the Noordermarkt, there is a market at the Westerstraat and at the Lindengracht. Around these areas there are a lot of traditional cafes and bars. The world famous Anne Frank Huis is located in this district. It is a biographical museum dedicated to Anne Frank, who was a diarist during the Second World War.

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is situated in the picturesque Rivierenbuurt neighbourhood of Amsterdam. The neighbourhood is situated in Amsterdam-Zuid, bordered by the river Amstel to the east, the Boerenwetering canal in the west, the Amstelkanaal in the north and the A10 motorway in the south.

The neighbourhood features many fine examples of Amsterdam School-architecture. The Dutch word Rivierenbuurt translates as 'Rivers Neighbourhood', which refers to the fact that most streets in the area are named after rivers in the Netherlands.

The apartment is literally across the street from the RAI convention center, very close to the train station and the metro 52, which takes you to the busiest centre of Amsterdam, literally in 7 minutes.
The apartment is also situated across the street from the finest restaurants and bars (best fish restaurant in town!).

Also like decoration and making my house  nice and cozy.
With friends we often indulge in a grilled meat or fish meal in restaurants nearby accompanied by a cold bottle of white wine. 
For travel or for work, come and try the true Amsterdam life,  I have a bunch of good tips for you :) Have fun!

My house is situated in the picturesque  Rivierenbuurt neighbourhood of Amsterdam city. The neighbourhood is bordered by the river Amstel. 
The neighbourhood features many fine examples of Amsterdam School-architecture. The Dutch word Rivierenbuurt translates as 'Rivers Neighbourhood', refers to the fact that most streets in the area are named after rivers in the Netherlands.

Until World War II the area had a sizable Jewish population which included Anne Frank and her family, who lived at Merwedeplein square until they went into hiding in the secret annex located in the Jordan.

Two minutes walking around my house you can be served by tram routes that takes you everywhere  in the city, such 4 and 12, bus routes 62 and 65, as well as Amsterdam metro and the train from Schiphol Airport, Amstel Station and Zuid Station. But if you want to try the real Amsterdam life you can always rent a bike just next door.


I’m sure you will have an amazing time !

neighborhood_overview: The apartment is located in a safe and cozy neighborhood with lots of nice restaurants, coffee places and shops within walking distance.
